<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	value-added,
</FONT>
	convenient and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	easy-to-prepare
</FONT>
</FONT>
	foods and the frequency in
	dining out. We are
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	well-positioned
</FONT>
	to benefit from these underlying growth trends, as well as emerging consumer preferences, given our product portfolio and segment orientation.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Business Mix
</I>
	. Our growth and profitability characteristics vary by product category and market segment. Therefore, changes in our mix may impact our profitability and growth profile as business mix is a component
	of our sales volume. For example, to the extent that our mix shifts towards higher
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	value-added
</FONT>
	products, such as breakfast sandwiches, our financial performance will be positively impacted. Further, our fourth
	segment, Industrial, opportunistically sells to other food producers under
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	short-term
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	co-manufacturing
</FONT>
	agreements based on our available capacity in order to optimize
	capacity utilization. Due to the lower margin nature of this business, we have strategically reduced our percentage of net sales generated by this segment to 5.0% in the 2016 YTD period.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Pricing Methodology
</I>
	. Our pricing is driven by the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	value-added
</FONT>
	nature of our products, our market share position and our differentiated value proposition to our customers
	due to our scale, broad product portfolio, customization capabilities, national distribution and food safety track record. Our financial performance depends on our ability to price effectively with our customers. We proactively adjust pricing
	frequently in order to reflect input cost movements with minimal lag time. In early 2014, we
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	re-engineered
</FONT>
	our pricing methodology and now utilize forward looking raw materials indices to set prices rather
	than trailing market indices. As a result, our pricing reflects our underlying raw materials costs in a more timely and accurate manner. Only 16.2% of our net sales in fiscal 2015 were subject to
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	annually-renewed
</FONT>
	fixed price arrangements and we have a high level of flexibility to adjust pricing across the remainder of our business.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We price our products through price list, index pricing and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	annually-renewed
</FONT>
	fixed price arrangements,
	which accounted for 76.1%, 7.7% and 16.2%, respectively, of our net sales in fiscal 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<U>
	Price List Arrangements
</U>
	. Our price list arrangements generally allow us to proactively update prices to reflect anticipated raw material prices, competitive dynamics and marketing strategies, subject to
	contractual limits on frequency and minimum notice requirements.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<U>
	Index Pricing Arrangements
</U>
	. Under these arrangements, we
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pass-through
</FONT>
	actual increases or decreases in raw material or conversion costs to our customers.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<U>
	Fixed Pricing Arrangements
</U>
	. These arrangements guarantee customers a fixed price for products for a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	contractually-set
</FONT>
	period of time, usually 12&nbsp;months. Our fixed
	prices for the agreed upon contractual term are based on forward looking raw materials indices and reflect expected raw material costs over the term of the contract.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Raw Material Costs
</I>
	. Raw material costs typically comprise approximately
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	three-fourths
</FONT>
	of our cost of goods sold, with beef, poultry and pork accounting for approximately
	half of our cost of goods sold. Other raw materials, such as bread and breadings, cheese, eggs, seasonings, soy proteins and packing, comprise the remainder. Raw material costs fluctuate due to changing market conditions and changing consumer
	preferences. Our results of operations will continue to depend on our ability to manage raw material cost movements through forward purchase orders, strategic sourcing,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cancelable
</FONT>
	contracts and by passing
	on such cost increases to customers.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	APF Way
</I>
	. Our APF Way continuous improvement program has revamped our cost structure, budgeting tools and pricing methodology. The APF Way uses a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	data-driven
</FONT>
	analytical
	framework to drive growth and profitability through improved commercial
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	decision-making,
</FONT>
	excellence in sales and marketing and productivity in procurement, logistics and production. We expect the APF Way will
	continue to be a key factor in our performance.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	52

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Components of Our Results of Operations
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Net Sales.
</I>
</B>
	Net sales consist of gross sales, which vary as a result of changes in volume and pricing, less certain costs that we
	manage as part of our trade promotion allowances, including:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Cash discounts, returns and other allowances; and
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Trade promotion allowances, which include the cost of temporary price reductions, as well as our customers&#146; costs for promotional displays and advertising space in store circulars.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Gross Profit.
</I>
</B>
	Gross profit is calculated as net sales less cost of goods sold, distribution expenses and restructuring expenses
	associated with our production and distribution network. For a discussion of restructuring expenses, see &#147;
<I>
	Restructuring expenses
</I>
	&#148; below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Cost of goods sold.
</I>
</B>
	Cost of goods sold includes the following:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Raw materials costs, including costs for proteins, such as beef, poultry, pork and other food ingredients such as bread and breadings, cheese, eggs, seasonings and soy proteins;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Packaging supply costs, including costs for corrugated fiberboard and plastic packaging materials; and
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Conversion costs, which represent all costs necessary to convert raw materials into finished product. Conversion costs include direct and indirect labor and plant overhead such as equipment rent, natural gas and other
	utilities, insurance, property taxes and depreciation. We periodically enter into hedging contracts to manage fluctuations in our natural gas costs, the effect of which is reflected in cost of goods sold.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Distribution expenses.
</I>
</B>
	We primarily use
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	third-party
</FONT>
	logistics providers to transport our
	products (1)&nbsp;among our production facilities, (2)&nbsp;from our production facilities to our distribution centers and (3)&nbsp;from our distribution centers and our production facilities to our customers. Our freight and distribution costs are
	influenced by diesel fuel costs as well as capacity within the industry. We periodically enter into hedging contracts to manage fluctuations in diesel fuel costs, the effect of which is reflected in distribution expenses. Distribution expense also
	includes warehousing costs related to our leased facility in Enid, Oklahoma and the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	third-party
</FONT>
	logistics providers we utilize (which are mainly in Cincinnati, Ohio and Rockmart, Georgia).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Selling, General and Administrative Expense.
</I>
</B>
	Selling, general and administrative expense includes the following:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Sales and marketing expenses, including salaries, wages and incentives for our sales and marketing personnel, broker commissions,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	sales-related
</FONT>
	travel and entertainment expenses
	and other marketing and advertising expenses. Our marketing programs also include costs relating to the execution of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	in-store
</FONT>
	product demonstrations, trade shows and samples provided to prospective customers;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	R&amp;D expenses, including salaries, wages and incentives for our internal R&amp;D personnel, and direct costs for external research and line testing;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	General and administrative expenses, including salaries, wages and incentives for our management and general administrative personnel, depreciation of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-production
</FONT>
	property and
	equipment, amortization of intangible assets, information technology licensing and maintenance costs, insurance, travel and other operating expenses;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Stock-based
</FONT>
	compensation expense related to stock awards granted to employees and directors. For a discussion of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	stock-based
</FONT>
	compensation
	expense, see &#147;Critical Accounting Policies and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Estimates&#151;Stock-Based
</FONT>
	Compensation&#148;;
</TD>

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<P ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Management, advisory and consulting fees and expense reimbursements paid, prior to our initial public offering,
	to Oaktree, and, prior to September&nbsp;30, 2015, to Maine Street Holdings,&nbsp;Inc., a management
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	53

<A NAME="eolPage60"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	company controlled by our minority stockholders. Upon consummation of our initial public offering, we paid Oaktree an aggregate success fee of $9.0&nbsp;million on July&nbsp;20, 2016 pursuant to
	the management services agreement, which was terminated on July&nbsp;20, 2016; and
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Professional fees to service providers including accounting and legal. As a recently registered public company, we have incurred, and will continue to incur, significant legal, accounting and other expenses that we did
	not incur as a private company, which will be reflected as selling, general and administrative expenses.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Restructuring expenses.
</I>
</B>
	From time to time, we initiate restructuring activities in order to integrate acquired businesses,
	improve the efficiency of our production and distribution network and consolidate and reorganize our management and support functions. For example:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	In fiscal 2012, we commenced the closure of our Orange City, Iowa production facility and consolidation of its activities into our network, all of which was substantially completed in fiscal 2013;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	In fiscal 2013, we undertook various initiatives intended to improve our commercial effectiveness and reduce operating costs. These initiatives continued into fiscal 2014 and fiscal 2015 and included:
	(1)&nbsp;consolidation of business unit leadership and shared service teams in our Cincinnati, Ohio area facilities and closure of our administrative office located in Edmond, Oklahoma; (2)&nbsp;reorganization of our senior leadership team; and
	(3)&nbsp;implementation of staffing reductions and facilities closures in production, logistics and commercial operations. The cost to implement these initiatives was incurred primarily in fiscal 2014; and
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	In fiscal 2015, we integrated the assets acquired from Landshire and Better Bakery and reconfigured production lines at our plant in Portland, Maine to
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	re-launch
</FONT>
	our
<I>
	Barber
</I>
	stuffed entr&eacute;es.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Expenses associated with restructuring initiatives affecting our production and distribution
	network are reflected as a separate cost component in determining gross profit. Expenses associated with restructuring initiatives affecting our selling, marketing and general administration functions are a separate cost component in determining
	operating income.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Benefit/Provision for income taxes.
</I>
</B>
	We are subject to U.S. federal income taxes and income taxes in
	certain states. However, we have favorable tax attributes, such as significant
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-deductible
</FONT>
	depreciation and amortization and U.S. federal and state net operating loss carryovers (&#147;NOLs&#148;), which
	resulted in minimal income tax expense and cash paid for income tax during fiscal 2015, fiscal 2014 and fiscal 2013. The majority of our income tax expense consists of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	provisions for deferred tax
	liabilities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In the second quarter of 2016 and Q3 2016, we continued the trend, that began in the first quarter of fiscal 2015, of
	realizing pretax income and our taxable cumulative income in the recent past became positive. In addition, our forecasts for the remainder of fiscal 2016 and for fiscal year 2017 indicate continued
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pre-tax
</FONT>
	income. Further, we were able to refinance our debt during the second quarter of fiscal 2016 on more favorable terms which will result in significant annual savings. After considering these factors, along with reviews of forecasts of future taxable
	income and expected utilization of tax attributes prior to their expiration, we determined that the positive evidence outweighed the negative evidence in the second quarter of fiscal 2016 and concluded, in the second quarter of fiscal 2016, that it
	was more likely than not that our deferred tax assets were realizable. As a result, we made the determination to release the full valuation allowance in fiscal 2016. Accordingly, we released $56.5&nbsp;million of the valuation allowance on a
	discrete basis during the second quarter of fiscal 2016 and, during Q3 2016, we released an additional $1.7&nbsp;million. The tax benefit associated with the remaining valuation allowance, along with a similar amount of tax expense connected to the
	reduction in the NOL deferred tax asset, will be released to income as profits are earned during the remainder of fiscal 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our
	effective tax rates for Q3 2016, Q3 2015 and for fiscal 2016 and fiscal 2015 are different from the expected federal rate of 35% in part due to the utilization of deferred tax assets and the release of the valuation allowances.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	54
</P>

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Key Performance Indicators
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Key performance indicators that we use to manage our business and evaluate our financial results and operating performance include:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Net Sales.
</I>
</B>
	We evaluate net sales on a consolidated basis and in each segment as a measure of volume growth, pricing
	effectiveness, business optimization and trade promotion allowance management.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Adjusted Net Income.
</I>
</B>
	Adjusted Net Income
	represents net income (loss) before interest expense, income tax expense, depreciation and amortization and certain non-cash and other adjustment items. We present Adjusted Net Income as a performance measure because we believe it facilitates a
	comparison of our operating performance on a consistent basis from
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	period-to-period
</FONT>
</FONT>
	and provides for a more complete understanding of factors and trends affecting our
	business than measures under GAAP can provide alone. We also believe that the presentation of Adjusted Net Income is useful to investors because it is frequently used by securities analysts, investors and other interested parties in their evaluation
	of the operating performance of companies in industries similar to ours. However, our definition of Adjusted Net Income may not be the same as similarly titled measures used by other companies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Adjusted Diluted Net Income Per Share.
</I>
</B>
	Adjusted Diluted Net Income Per Share represents the diluted per share value of Adjusted
	Net Income. We present Adjusted Diluted Net Income Per Share as a performance measure because we believe it facilitates a comparison of our operating performance on a consistent basis from
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	period-to-period
</FONT>
</FONT>
	and provides for a more complete understanding of factors and trends affecting our business than measures under GAAP can provide alone. We also believe that the presentation of Adjusted
	Diluted Net Income Per Share is useful to investors because it is frequently used by securities analysts, investors and other interested parties in their evaluation of the operating performance of companies in industries similar to ours. However,
	our definition of Adjusted Diluted Net Income Per Share may not be the same as similarly titled measures used by other companies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Adjusted EBITDA.
</I>
</B>
	&nbsp;Adjusted EBITDA represents net income (loss) before interest expense, income tax expense and depreciation
	and amortization, as well as certain
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	and other adjustment items. We present Adjusted EBITDA as a performance measure because we believe it facilitates a comparison of our operating performance on a
	consistent basis from
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	period-to-period
</FONT>
</FONT>
	and provides for a more complete understanding of factors and trends affecting our business than measures under GAAP can provide
	alone. We also believe that Adjusted EBITDA is useful to investors in evaluating our operating performance because it provides a means to evaluate the operating performance of our business on an ongoing basis using criteria that our management uses
	for evaluation and planning purposes. Because Adjusted EBITDA facilitates internal comparisons of our historical financial position and operating performance on a more consistent basis, our management also uses Adjusted EBITDA in measuring our
	performance relative to that of our competitors, in communications with our board of directors concerning our operating performance and in evaluating acquisition opportunities. In addition, targets for Adjusted EBITDA are among the measures we use
	to evaluate our management&#146;s performance for purposes of determining their compensation. We also believe that the presentation of Adjusted EBITDA is useful to investors because it is frequently used by securities analysts, investors and other
	interested parties in their evaluation of the operating performance of companies in industries similar to ours. However, our definition of Adjusted EBITDA may not be the same as similarly titled measures used by other companies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Adjusted Net Income, Adjusted Diluted Net Income Per Share and Adjusted EBITDA are
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-GAAP
</FONT>
	financial
	measures. See &#147;Prospectus Summary&#151;Summary Historical Consolidated Financial Data&#148; for additional information including reconciliations to the most directly comparable GAAP measure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	55
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Q3 2016 compared to Q3 2015
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Net sales.
</I>
	Net sales for Q3 2016 were $393.7&nbsp;million, a decrease of $13.5&nbsp;million, or 3.3%, compared to $407.2&nbsp;million
	for Q3 2015. Net sales decreased by $4.7&nbsp;million, or 1.1%, due to changes in sales volume and business mix, and $8.8&nbsp;million, or 2.2%, due to lower average sales prices.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Sales volume was lower due to the elimination of sales under lower margin contracts in our Industrial segment which reduced net sales by
	$14.0&nbsp;million. Excluding the impact of Industrial segment volume, changes in volume and business mix in our three core segments increased net sales by $9.3&nbsp;million, with sales volume growth increasing net sales for our three core segments
	by 0.7%, and changes in business mix increasing net sales for our three core segments by 1.8%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Cost of goods sold.
</I>
	Cost of goods
	sold for Q3 2016 was $264.5&nbsp;million, a decrease of $28.5&nbsp;million, or 9.7%, compared to $293.0&nbsp;million for Q3 2015. As a percent of net sales, cost of goods sold was 67.2% in Q3 2016 compared with 72.0% in Q3 2015, a reduction of 480
	basis points. Cost of goods sold decreased by $5.7&nbsp;million due to lower sales volume, $3.8&nbsp;million due to productivity improvements and $20.1&nbsp;million due to lower raw materials costs. The decrease in cost of goods sold was partially
	offset by higher other input costs, such as labor inflation, utilities and other manufacturing costs, which increased cost of goods sold by $1.1&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Distribution expenses.
</I>
	Distribution expenses for Q3 2016 were $23.7&nbsp;million, a decrease of $1.2&nbsp;million, or 4.8%, compared to
	distribution expenses of $24.9&nbsp;million for Q3 2015. Distribution expenses decreased by $0.8&nbsp;million due to lower sales volume, and by a similar amount due to productivity changes. The decrease in distribution expenses was partially offset
	by higher administrative costs of $0.4&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	56
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Gross profit.
</I>
	Gross profit for Q3 2016 increased by $17.7&nbsp;million to
	$105.4&nbsp;million, or 26.8% of net sales, compared to $87.7&nbsp;million, or 21.5% of net sales, for Q3 2015, reflecting an increase of 530&nbsp;basis points. Gross profit increased primarily due to productivity improvements, positive price
	realization net of raw material cost movements and contributions from volume. The following table outlines the factors that impacted our gross profit:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Non-cash
</FONT>
	stock compensation expense includes
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	one-time
</FONT>
	initial public offering related charges of $6.5&nbsp;million related to the change in the fair value of unvested restricted stock and $2.9&nbsp;million of charges related to the acceleration of certain
	restricted stock awards. The remainder of the expense relates to normal vesting of stock awards.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Other expense, net.
</I>
	Other
	expense, net for Q3 2016 consisted primarily of the $9.0&nbsp;million success fee paid to Oaktree and certain public filing expenses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Interest expense.
</I>
	Interest expense for Q3 2016 was $18.7&nbsp;million, a decrease of $7.2&nbsp;million, compared to $25.9&nbsp;million
	for Q3 2015. This decrease was a result of lower average borrowings and the benefit of lower rates on the refinanced debt. Lower average borrowings were as a result of the voluntary repayment of $205.0&nbsp;million of our first lien term loan from
	the initial public offering proceeds and stronger cash flow from operations. These decreases were partially offset by the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	write-off
</FONT>
	of deferred financing fees and original issue discount of $3.4&nbsp;million,
	in aggregate, related to the $205.0&nbsp;million prepayment of our first lien term loan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Income tax benefit/provision.
</I>
	We
	recognized a tax benefit of $1.8&nbsp;million in Q3 2016, which resulted in an effective federal tax rate of (8.9)%. The significant improvement over the effective federal tax rate of 19.2% for Q3 2015 was due to the utilization of deferred tax
	assets and the release of valuation allowances that were discussed above in this Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Net
	income.
</I>
	Net income for Q3 2016 was $22.4&nbsp;million, an increase of $9.8&nbsp;million compared to $12.6&nbsp;million for Q3 2015. This improvement in net income was a result of the factors discussed above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	57
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage64"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	2016 YTD Period compared to 2015 YTD Period
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Net Sales.
</I>
	Net sales for the 2016 YTD period were $1,158.8&nbsp;million, a decrease of $66.8&nbsp;million, or 5.4%, compared to
	$1,225.6&nbsp;million for the 2015 YTD period. Net sales decreased by $32.6&nbsp;million, or 2.7%, due to changes in sales volume and business mix, and $34.1&nbsp;million, or 2.8%, due to lower average sales prices.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Sales volume was lower due to the elimination of sales under lower margin contracts in our Industrial segment, which reduced net sales by
	$46.5&nbsp;million. Excluding the impact of Industrial segment volume, changes in volume and business mix in our three core segments increased net sales by $13.9&nbsp;million, with sales volume growth increasing net sales for our three core segments
	by 1.8% and changes in business mix reducing net sales for our three core segments by 0.5%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Average sales prices decreased due to
	strategic price and trade spending investments to reflect lower raw material costs, which reduced net sales by $34.1&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Cost of goods sold.
</I>
	Cost of goods sold for the 2016 YTD period was $783.5&nbsp;million, a decrease of $108.0&nbsp;million, or 12.1%,
	compared to $891.5&nbsp;million for the 2015 YTD period. As a percent of net sales, cost of goods sold was 67.6% in the 2016 YTD period compared with 72.7% in the 2015 YTD period, a reduction of 510 basis points. Cost of goods sold decreased by
	$29.8&nbsp;million due to lower sales volume, $23.7&nbsp;million due to productivity improvements and $64.6&nbsp;million due to lower raw materials costs. The decrease in cost of goods sold was partially offset by higher other input costs, such as
	labor inflation, utilities and other manufacturing costs, which increased cost of goods sold by $10.1&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Distribution
	expenses.
</I>
	Distribution expenses for the 2016 YTD period were $68.7&nbsp;million, a decrease of $4.4&nbsp;million, or 6.0%, compared to distribution expenses of $73.1&nbsp;million for the 2015 YTD period. Distribution expenses decreased by
	$1.8&nbsp;million due to lower sales volume and $2.7&nbsp;million due to productivity, which were partially offset by higher administrative costs of $0.1&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Gross profit.
</I>
	Gross profit for the 2016 YTD period increased by $47.9&nbsp;million to $306.6&nbsp;million, or 26.5% of net sales
	compared to $258.7&nbsp;million, or 21.1% of net sales, for the 2015 YTD period, reflecting an increase of 540 basis points. Gross profit increased primarily due to productivity improvements and positive price realization net of raw material cost
	movements and contributions from volume, partially offset by other increases in costs of goods sold. The following table outlines the factors that impacted our gross profit:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_14"></A>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="76%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="63%">
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="15%">
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="14%">
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
<TD>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM">

<I>
	Selling, general and administrative expenses.
</I>
	Selling, general and administrative expenses
	for the 2016 YTD period were $165.4&nbsp;million, or 14.3% of net sales, compared with $142.4&nbsp;million, or 11.6% of net sales, for the 2015 YTD period. The primary factors impacting selling, general and administrative expenses are summarized in
	the table below:

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Non-cash
</FONT>
	stock compensation expense includes
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	one-time
</FONT>
	initial public offering related charges of $6.5&nbsp;million related to the change in the fair value of unvested restricted stock and $2.9&nbsp;million of charges related to the acceleration of certain
	restricted stock awards. The remainder of the expense relates to normal vesting of stock awards.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Other expense, net.
</I>
	Other
	expense, net for the 2016 YTD period consisted primarily of the $9.0&nbsp;million success fee paid to Oaktree, in connection with our initial public offering, and certain public filing expenses. Other expense, net for the 2015 YTD period consisted
	primarily of acquisition integration and merger and acquisition expenses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Interest expense.
</I>
	Interest expense for the 2016 YTD
	period was $82.5&nbsp;million, an increase of $3.8&nbsp;million, compared to $78.7&nbsp;million for the 2015 YTD period. This increase resulted from the $15.4&nbsp;million of charges related to the refinancing of our credit facilities, including the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	write-off
</FONT>
	of $1.4&nbsp;million related to deferred loan fees, $0.8&nbsp;million related to original issue discount, $1.2&nbsp;million of prepayment penalties related to our prior term loans and
	$11.9&nbsp;million of charges related to third party fees for our first lien term loan. Interest expense also increased as a result of the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	write-off
</FONT>
	of deferred financing fees and original issue discount of
	$3.4&nbsp;million, in aggregate, related to the repayment of $205.0&nbsp;million of our first lien term loan. These increases were partially offset by the benefit of lower rates on the refinanced debt and lower average borrowings as compared to the
	prior period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Income tax benefit/provision.
</I>
	We recognized a tax benefit of $58.2&nbsp;million in the 2016 YTD period, which
	resulted in an effective federal tax rate of (129.3)%. The significant improvement over the effective federal tax rate of 19.2% for the 2015 YTD period was primarily due to the utilization of deferred tax assets and the release of valuation
	allowances that was discussed above in this Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Net income.
</I>
	Net income for the 2016 YTD
	period was $103.1&nbsp;million, an increase of $77.7&nbsp;million, compared to $25.4&nbsp;million for the 2015 YTD period. This increase in net income was a result of the factors discussed above, primarily the utilization of deferred tax assets and
	the release of valuation allowances.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Fiscal 2015 compared to Fiscal 2014
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Net sales.
</I>
	Net sales for fiscal 2015 were $1,611.6&nbsp;million, an increase of $34.0&nbsp;million, or 2.2%, compared to
	$1,577.6&nbsp;million of net sales for fiscal 2014. Net sales increased by $76.0&nbsp;million, or 4.8%, due to higher average sales prices, partially offset by changes in sales volume and business mix, which reduced net sales by $42.0&nbsp;million,
	or 2.6%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Sales volume was lower due to the elimination of sales under lower margin contracts in our Industrial segment, which reduced net
	sales by $63.1&nbsp;million, and the absence of a 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week, which reduced net sales by
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	59
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage66"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	$31.4&nbsp;million, partially offset by sales volume attributable to acquisitions, which increased net sales by $48.9&nbsp;million. Excluding these items, changes in sales volume and business mix
	contributed $3.6&nbsp;million to net sales.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Average sales prices increased due to a series of strategic pricing actions to recover higher
	raw material costs, which increased net sales by $54.8&nbsp;million, and the benefit of more effective trade promotion allowance management, resulting in lower sales discounts, which increased net sales by $21.2&nbsp;million. Average sales prices
	increased across our segments largely due to the continued effect of the significant increase in protein costs in 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Cost of goods
	sold.
</I>
	Cost of goods sold for fiscal 2015 was $1,158.2&nbsp;million, a decrease of $68.9&nbsp;million, or 5.6%, compared to $1,227.1&nbsp;million of cost of goods sold for fiscal 2014. Cost of goods sold decreased by $46.3&nbsp;million due to
	lower sales volume and $44.3&nbsp;million due to productivity improvements. The decrease in cost of goods sold was partially offset by higher raw material costs, which increased cost of goods sold by $21.7&nbsp;million. Higher raw material costs
	were primarily driven by increases in the cost of protein.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Distribution expenses.
</I>
	Distribution expenses for fiscal 2015 was
	$96.5&nbsp;million, a decrease of $2.8&nbsp;million, or 2.8%, compared to $99.3&nbsp;million of distribution expenses in fiscal 2014. Distribution expenses increased by $0.1&nbsp;million due to lower sales volume and $6.4&nbsp;million due to
	productivity improvements, which was partially offset by an increase of $3.5&nbsp;million due to higher warehouse costs and inflation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Gross profit.
</I>
	Gross profit for fiscal 2015 increased by $105.2&nbsp;million to $354.4&nbsp;million, or 22.0% of net sales, compared to
	$249.2&nbsp;million, or 15.8% of net sales, for fiscal 2014, reflecting an increase of 620 basis points. Gross profit increased primarily due to more effective trade promotion allowance management and other productivity improvements, positive price
	realization net of raw material cost movements, and contributions from acquisitions, partially offset by increases in distribution expenses and the absence of a 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week. The following table
	outlines the factors that impacted our gross profit:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_16"></A>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="63%">
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="14%">
</TD>

</TD>

</TD>

</TD>
<TD>
</TD>

<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Selling, general and administrative expenses.
</I>
	Selling, general and administrative expenses for fiscal
	2015 were $196.2&nbsp;million, or 12.2% of net sales, compared with $167.6&nbsp;million, or 10.6% of net sales, for fiscal 2014. The primary factors impacting selling, general, and administrative expenses are summarized in the table below:
</P>

<A NAME="eolPage67"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Other expense, net.
</I>
	Other expense, net for fiscal 2015 consisted primarily of
	$6.2&nbsp;million of acquisition expenses and $1.2&nbsp;million of loss on disposal of property, plant and equipment, partially offset by $2.0&nbsp;million of income associated with a product recall claim, net of deductibles, under our product
	contamination insurance policy.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Interest expense.
</I>
	Interest expense was $104.4&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015, a decrease of
	$1.2&nbsp;million, or 1.1%, compared to $105.6&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014. This decrease was due to lower average outstanding borrowings under our prior term loans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Provision for income taxes.
</I>
	We paid minimal cash for income tax in both fiscal 2015 and fiscal 2014 because in fiscal 2014 we incurred
	a $14.8&nbsp;million operating loss, net of taxes, and in fiscal 2015 we utilized $14.6&nbsp;million of net operating loss carryovers, net of taxes, to offset taxable income. Income tax expense for fiscal 2015 was $8.9&nbsp;million compared to
	$8.4&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014, which in each case related primarily to recognition of deferred income tax liabilities and current state taxes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Net income (loss).
</I>
	&nbsp;Net income for fiscal 2015 was $37.1&nbsp;million, an increase of $75.0&nbsp;million, compared with a net loss
	of $37.9&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014. This improvement in net income was a result of the factors discussed above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Fiscal 2014
	compared to Fiscal 2013
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Net sales.
</I>
	Net sales for fiscal 2014 were $1,577.6&nbsp;million, an increase of $85.6&nbsp;million,
	or 5.7%, compared to $1,492.0&nbsp;million for fiscal 2013. Net sales increased by $90.2&nbsp;million, or 6.0%, due to higher average sales prices, partially offset by changes in sales volume and business mix, which reduced net sales by
	$4.6&nbsp;million, or 0.3%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Sales volume was lower due to the elimination of sales under lower margin contracts in our Industrial
	segment, which reduced net sales by $63.0&nbsp;million, partially offset by sales volume attributable to the addition of a 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week, which increased net sales by $31.4&nbsp;million.
	Excluding these items, changes in sales volume and business mix contributed $27.0&nbsp;million to net sales.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Average sales prices
	increased due to a series of strategic pricing actions to recover higher raw material costs, which increased net sales by $76.3&nbsp;million, and the benefit of more effective trade promotion allowance management, resulting in lower sales discounts,
	which increased net sales by $13.8&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Cost of goods sold.
</I>
	Cost of goods sold for fiscal 2014 was $1,227.1&nbsp;million,
	an increase of $82.8&nbsp;million, or 7.2%, compared to $1,144.3&nbsp;million of cost of goods sold for fiscal 2013. Cost of goods sold increased by $102.8&nbsp;million due to higher raw material costs and $27.0&nbsp;million due to higher other
	input costs, such as labor and employee benefit expenses, utility bills and other manufacturing costs. The increase in cost of goods sold was partially offset by lower sales volume, which reduced cost of goods sold by $19.6&nbsp;million, and
	productivity improvements, which reduced cost of goods sold by $27.4&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Distribution expenses.
</I>
	Distribution expenses
	for fiscal 2014 was $99.3&nbsp;million, an increase of $4.0&nbsp;million, or 4.2%, compared to $95.3&nbsp;million of distribution expenses in fiscal 2013. Distribution expenses increased by $2.2&nbsp;million due to sales volume and $5.3&nbsp;million
	due to higher warehouse costs and inflation, which was partially offset by a decrease of $3.5&nbsp;million due to productivity improvements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Gross profit.
</I>
	Gross profit for fiscal 2014 increased by $18.3&nbsp;million to $249.2&nbsp;million, or 15.8% of net sales, compared to
	$230.9&nbsp;million, or 15.5% of net sales, for fiscal 2013, reflecting an increase of 30&nbsp;basis points. Gross profit increased primarily due to more effective trade promotion allowance management and other productivity improvements and the
	addition of a 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week, partially offset by negative price realization net of
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	61
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage68"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	raw material cost movements, and other increases in cost of goods sold and distribution expenses. The following table outlines the impact of the factors that impacted our gross profit:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>

<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" COLSPAN="2" ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1.00PT SOLID #000000">
<B>
	Change&nbsp;in
<BR>
	Gross&nbsp;Profit
<BR>
	(in millions)
</B>
</TD>

	Selling, general and administrative expenses.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Other expense, net.
</I>
	Other expense, net was not a significant factor in either fiscal 2014 or fiscal
	2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Interest expense.
</I>
	Interest expense was $105.6&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014, an increase of $1.0&nbsp;million, or 1.0%,
	compared to $104.6&nbsp;million for fiscal 2013. This increase was due to higher average outstanding borrowings under our ABL facility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Provision for income taxes.
</I>
	We paid minimal cash for income tax in both fiscal 2014 and fiscal 2013 because we incurred net operating
	losses in both years, net of taxes, of $14.8&nbsp;million and $31.3&nbsp;million, respectively. Income tax expense for fiscal 2014 was $8.4&nbsp;million compared to $6.3&nbsp;million in fiscal 2013, which in each case related primarily to
	recognition of deferred income tax liabilities and current state taxes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Net income (loss).
</I>
	&nbsp;Net loss for fiscal 2014 was
	$37.9&nbsp;million, a reduction of $19.1&nbsp;million, compared with a net loss of $57.0&nbsp;million for fiscal 2013. This improvement in net income was a result of the factors discussed above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	62
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Sales volume.
</I>
	Sales volume for Q3 2016 and the 2016 YTD period decreased due to lower
	demand for fruit cups in schools and slower restaurant traffic affecting our national chains and street customers, partially offset by growth in school sandwich and protein categories.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Average sales price.
</I>
	Sales prices for Q3 2016 and the 2016 YTD period decreased due to strategic price and trade spend
	investments to reflect lower raw material costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating income.
</I>
	Operating income and operating margins improved
	in Q3 2016 and for the 2016 YTD period due to productivity improvements and positive price realization net of raw material and other input cost movements, partially offset by the decline in sales volume.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	63
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Sales volume.
</I>
	Sales volume increased in Q3 2016 compared to Q3 2015 primarily as a
	result of growth in high
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	value-added
</FONT>
	stuffed entrees, partially offset by reduced promotional sales and rationalization of certain private label
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	fully-cooked
</FONT>
	breaded
	poultry SKUs. In addition, volume in Q3 2016 was more favorable than Q3 2015 due to the adverse effects in Q3 2015 of the product recall. Sales volume increased for the 2016 YTD period compared to the 2015 YTD period due to new product placements
	and promotional events.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Average sales price.
</I>
	Average sales price decreased due to strategic price investments to
	reflect lower raw material costs and trade promotion allowances to support growth initiatives.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating income.
</I>
	Operating income and operating margin for Q3 2016 and the 2016 YTD period improved primarily as a result of higher volume sales, productivity improvements, and positive price realization net of raw material movements.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Sales volume.
</I>
	Sales volume for Q3 2016 and the 2016 YTD period increased due to higher
	volume across our key product categories due to new product placements and existing customers opening new locations. In addition, fiscal 2015 acquisitions increased net sales for the 2016 YTD period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

</I>
	Average sales prices for Q3 2016 and the 2016 YTD period decreased due to strategic price and trade
	investments to reflect lower raw material costs.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating income.
</I>
	Operating income and operating margin for Q3
	2016 and the 2016 YTD period improved, primarily as a result of higher sales volume, productivity improvements, and positive price realization net of raw material movements.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Sales volume.
</I>
	Sales volume for Q3 2016 and the 2016 YTD period decreased primarily due
	to the elimination of sales under lower margin contracts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Average sales price.
</I>
	Average sales prices for Q3 2016 and
	the 2016 YTD period decreased due to index pricing adjustment to reflect lower raw material costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating income.
</I>
	Operating income and operating margin for the 2016 YTD period increased primarily due to the elimination of lower margin contracts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Fiscal 2015 compared to Fiscal 2014
</I>
</B>
</P>

</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="BOTTOM">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</TD>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Sales volume.
</I>
	Foodservice sales volume was lower due to the absence of a 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week, which reduced Foodservice net sales by $16.9&nbsp;million, partially offset by Foodservice sales volume attributable to acquisitions, which increased Foodservice net sales by
	$2.5&nbsp;million. Excluding these items, changes in sales volume and business mix contributed $8.3&nbsp;million to Foodservice net sales primarily due to increased volume with schools and restaurant chains, partially offset by a small decrease in
	volume with certain foodservice distributors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Average sales price.
</I>
	Foodservice average sales prices increased due
	to a series of strategic pricing actions to recover higher raw material costs, which increased Foodservice net sales by $49.8&nbsp;million, and the benefit of more effective trade promotion allowance management, which increased Foodservice net sales
	by $12.8&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating income.
</I>
	Foodservice operating income margin increased primarily due to more
	effective trade promotion allowance management and other productivity improvements and positive price realization net of raw material and other input cost movements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	65
</P>

<TD VALIGN="TOP">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Sales volume.
</I>
	Retail sales volume was lower due to the absence of a 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week, which reduced Retail net sales by $7.6&nbsp;million, partially offset by Retail sales volume attributable to acquisitions, which increased Retail net sales by $14.8&nbsp;million.
	Excluding these items, changes in sales volume and business mix reduced Retail net sales by $14.4&nbsp;million primarily due to a temporary decline in sales of stuffed entr&eacute;es following a product recall during fiscal 2015, partially offset by
	increased private label sandwich volume.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Average sales price.
</I>
	Retail average sales prices increased due to more
	effective trade promotion allowance management, which increased Retail net sales by $7.0&nbsp;million, partially offset by strategic price decreases, which reduced Retail net sales by $3.4&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating income.
</I>
	Retail operating income margin increased primarily due to more effective trade promotion allowance
	management and other productivity improvements and positive price realization net of raw material and other input costs movements.
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Sales volume.
</I>
	Convenience sales volume was lower due to the absence of a 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week, which reduced Convenience net sales by $3.2&nbsp;million, partially offset by Convenience sales volume attributable to acquisitions, which increased Convenience net sales by
	$31.4&nbsp;million. Excluding these items, changes in sales volume and business mix contributed $9.9&nbsp;million to Convenience net sales primarily due to higher volume across our main product categories as a result of new customers and existing
	customers opening new locations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Average sales price.
</I>
	Convenience average sales prices increased due to a series of
	strategic pricing actions to recover higher raw material costs, which increased Convenience net sales by $2.6&nbsp;million, and the benefit of more effective trade promotion allowance management, which increased Convenience net sales by
	$1.4&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating income.
</I>
	Convenience operating income margin increased primarily due to more effective
	trade promotion allowance management and other productivity improvements and positive price realization net of raw material and other input cost movements.
</P>

	&nbsp;

<I>
	Sales volume.
</I>
	Industrial sales volume was lower due to the elimination of sales under
	lower margin contracts, which reduced Industrial net sales by $63.1&nbsp;million, and the absence of a 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week, which reduced Industrial net sales by $3.7&nbsp;million.

	Average sales price.
</I>
	Industrial average sales prices increased due to index pricing increases to reflect higher raw
	material costs, which increased Industrial net sales by $5.8&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating income.
</I>
	Industrial operating
	income margin increased primarily due to the elimination of lower margin contracts and pricing actions to recover historical cost inflation.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Sales volume.
</I>
	Foodservice sales volume attributable to the addition of a 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week increased Foodservice net sales by $16.9&nbsp;million. Excluding the impact of the additional 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week, changes in sales volume
	and business mix contributed $13.2&nbsp;million to Foodservice net sales primarily due to increased sales volume with schools and restaurant chains and other foodservice distributors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Average sales price.
</I>
	Foodservice average sales prices increased due to a series of strategic pricing actions to recover
	higher raw material costs, which increased Foodservice net sales by $54.6&nbsp;million, and the benefit of more effective trade promotion allowance management, which increased Foodservice net sales by $4.0&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating income.
</I>
	Foodservice operating income margin increased primarily due to more effective trade promotion
	allowance management and other productivity improvements, partially offset by negative price realization net of raw material and other input cost movements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Sales volume.
</I>
	Retail sales volume attributable to the addition of a 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week increased Retail net sales by $7.6&nbsp;million. Excluding the impact of the additional 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week, changes in sales volume and
	business mix contributed $2.6&nbsp;million to Retail net sales primarily due to increased volume of private label sandwiches and other entr&eacute;es and branded stuffed entr&eacute;es, partially offset by the impact of a strategic SKU
	rationalization as part of the APF Way that was substantially executed during the fourth quarter of fiscal 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Average sales price.
</I>
	Retail average sales prices increased due to a series of strategic pricing actions to recover
	higher raw material costs, which increased Retail net sales by $1.0&nbsp;million, and the benefit of more effective trade promotion allowance management, which increased Retail net sales by $9.4&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating income.
</I>
	Retail operating income margin increased primarily due to SKU rationalization, more effective trade
	promotion allowance management and other productivity improvements, partially offset by negative price realization net of raw material and other input cost movements.
</P>

<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week increased Convenience net sales by $3.2&nbsp;million. Excluding the impact of the additional 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week, changes in sales volume
	and business mix contributed $11.2&nbsp;million to Convenience net sales primarily due to increased volume in sandwiches and sandwich components as a result of new customers and existing customers opening new locations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Average sales price.
</I>
	Convenience average sales prices increased due to a series of strategic pricing actions to recover
	higher raw material costs, which increased Convenience net sales by $6.3&nbsp;million, and the benefit of more effective trade promotion allowance management, which increased Convenience net sales by $0.4&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	Operating Income.
</I>
	Convenience operating income margin increased primarily due to more effective trade promotion
	allowance management and other productivity improvements, partially offset by negative price realization net of raw material and other input cost movements.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Sales volume.
</I>
	Industrial sales volume was lower due to the elimination of sales under
	lower margin contracts, which reduced Industrial net sales by $63.0&nbsp;million, partially offset by Industrial sales volume attributable to the addition of a 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	&nbsp;week, which increased
	Industrial net sales by $3.7&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Average sales price.
</I>
	Industrial average sales prices increased due to
	index pricing increases to reflect higher raw material costs, which increased Industrial net sales by $14.5&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating income.
</I>
	Industrial operating income margin increased primarily due to the elimination of sales under lower
	margin contracts and pricing actions to recover historical cost inflation.
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_33"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Adjusted Net Income, Adjusted Diluted Net Income Per Share and Adjusted EBITDA are
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-GAAP
</FONT>
	financial measures. See &#147;Prospectus Summary&#151;Summary Historical Consolidated Financial Data&#148; for additional information including reconciliations to the most directly comparable GAAP measure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Quarterly Results and Seasonality
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our quarterly operating results are affected by seasonal fluctuations in our net sales and operating income. Sales to schools accounted for
	16.7% of our consolidated net sales and 30.7% of our Foodservice segment net sales in the 2016 YTD period. Because schools comprise a significant portion (approximately 20%) of our customer base, sales of our products tend to be lower during the
	summer months and rise significantly during the autumn &#147;back to school&#148; period. In addition, seasonal fluctuations in the demand for beef and other proteins tend to cause seasonal variations in raw material costs, which tend to rise in the
	winter and spring and decline during the summer months. The seasonality factors can cause our operating results and use of cash for working capital requirements to fluctuate during the fiscal year, with our working capital balances typically rising
	in the first three quarters of the year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	69
</P>
