<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	John N. Simons, Jr.
</I>
</B>
	John N. Simons, Jr. has been our Chief Executive Officer and a member of our
	board of directors since October 2013. Mr. Simons also served as our President from October&nbsp;2013 to November&nbsp;2016. Prior to joining us, Mr.&nbsp;Simons led Fir Hill Ventures,&nbsp;LLC, a consulting firm founded by Mr.&nbsp;Simons that
	advises beef industry participants on developing domestic and international growth strategies, from December 2010 to October 2013. Prior to his leadership at Fir Hill Ventures, Mr.&nbsp;Simons served in a variety of leadership roles in agribusiness,
	food and consumer products at Gregory Mountain Products, Swift&nbsp;&amp; Company,&nbsp;Inc., ConAgra Foods,&nbsp;Inc. and Cargill,&nbsp;Inc. Mr.&nbsp;Simons was President and Chief Executive Officer of Gregory Mountain Products from 2006 to 2009,
	President and Chief Executive Officer of Swift&nbsp;&amp; Company,&nbsp;Inc. from 2002 to 2005 and President and Chief Operating Officer of ConAgra Foods&#146; red meat division from 1999 to 2002. Prior to joining ConAgra Foods, Mr.&nbsp;Simons held
	a variety of general manager roles at Cargill,&nbsp;Inc. in the United States, Canada and Australia from 1991 to 1999. Mr.&nbsp;Simons previously served on the board of LiveNation Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc. from 2005 to 2007, where he chaired the
	compensation committee and served on its audit committee. Mr.&nbsp;Simons holds a Bachelor of Arts in Economics and Political Science from Stanford University and a Master of Business Administration from Harvard University.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Christopher D. Sliva.
</I>
</B>
	Christopher D. Sliva became our President and a member of our board of directors in November 2016. Prior
	to joining us, Mr.&nbsp;Sliva was President and Chief Operating Officer of TreeHouse Foods,&nbsp;Inc., a consumer packaged food and beverage manufacturer. Mr.&nbsp;Sliva joined TreeHouse in July 2012 as Senior Vice President and Chief Operating
	Officer of TreeHouse&#146;s Bay Valley Foods operating unit. Mr.&nbsp;Sliva also served as Executive Vice President and Chief Operating Officer of TreeHouse and as President of Bay Valley during his time at TreeHouse. Prior to joining TreeHouse,
	Mr.&nbsp;Sliva held various positions for Dean Foods Company from March 2006 to June 2012, including as Chief Customer Officer for the White Wave Foods
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	99

	division of Dean Foods and President and Chief Operating Officer for the Morningstar division of Dean Foods. Prior to joining Dean Foods, Mr.&nbsp;Sliva held various leadership roles and sales
	and marketing positions with Eastman Kodak Company, Fort James Corporation and Procter&nbsp;&amp; Gamble Distributing Company. Mr.&nbsp;Sliva holds a Bachelor of Science degree in Business Administration from Washington University.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Michael B. Sims.
</I>
</B>
	Michael B. Sims became our Senior Vice President, Chief Financial Officer and Treasurer in February 2012. Prior
	to joining us, Mr.&nbsp;Sims spent more than two decades in accounting, financial operations, investor relations and corporate development roles with Chiquita Brands International,&nbsp;Inc. From August 2009 to February 2012, Mr.&nbsp;Sims served as
	Senior Vice President and Chief Financial Officer of Chiquita. Prior to joining Chiquita in September 1988, Mr.&nbsp;Sims served as manager of financial reporting at Staley and in the audit department of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young. Mr.&nbsp;Sims
	presently serves on the board of directors for the Dan Beard Council, Boy Scouts of America. Mr.&nbsp;Sims holds a Bachelor of Science degree in Accounting from Indiana University and successfully completed the Certified Public Accountant exam.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	George F. Chappelle, Jr.
</I>
</B>
	George F. Chappelle, Jr. became our Chief Operating Officer in November 2016. In this role,
	Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle is responsible for overseeing our production operations and supply chain as well as all business development activities, including acquisitions, divestitures and other strategic projects. Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle joined us in January
	2014 as Senior Vice President, Supply Chain. Prior to joining us, Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle served as Chief Operating Officer of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Vi-Jon,&nbsp;Inc.
</FONT>
	from January 2013 to December 2013 and as Chief Operating Officer of
	Solo Cup&nbsp;Co. from October 2009 to September 2012. Prior to joining Solo Cup&nbsp;Co., Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle worked for H.J. Heinz Company and Sara Lee Corporation, most recently as Chief Supply Chain Officer for the North American Division of Sara
	Lee. Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle began his career with The Gillette Company. Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle holds a Bachelor of Science degree from Westfield State University and a Master of Science degree from Lesley University.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	James L. Clough.
</I>
</B>
	James L. Clough became our President, Foodservice in July 2013 and our Chief Commercial Officer in November
	2016. In these roles, Mr.&nbsp;Clough will continue to lead the sales, marketing and financing functions for our foodservice business and will have additional leadership responsibilities related to our
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	customer-centric
</FONT>
	efforts. Prior to joining us, Mr.&nbsp;Clough served as President, Foodservice at Schwan&#146;s Food Service&nbsp;Inc. from June 2010 to July 2013. Prior to joining Schwan&#146;s Food,
	Mr.&nbsp;Clough was President of Fresh Start Bakeries from January 2008 to October 2010. Mr.&nbsp;Clough has also served in senior leadership positions at Bunge Foods Group, Heinz Foodservice and ConAgra Foods. Mr.&nbsp;Clough presently serves on
	the board of directors for Kwik Trip,&nbsp;Inc. and is also the chairman of the audit committee. Mr.&nbsp;Clough previously served on the board of directors of the School Nutrition Foundation, the International Foodservice Manufacturers Association
	and the Global Child Nutrition Foundation. Mr.&nbsp;Clough received his Bachelor of Science degree in Industrial Management from the University of Akron and a Master&#146;s degree in Liberal Arts from Baker University. Mr.&nbsp;Clough is also
	accredited by the School Nutrition Association as a School Nutrition Specialist.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Steven D. Booker.
</I>
</B>
	Steven D. Booker became
	our President, Retail in November 2015. Prior to joining us, Mr.&nbsp;Booker served as Senior Vice President, Customer Development at ConAgra Foods from June 2014 to November 2015. In this role, Mr.&nbsp;Booker led the customer development team,
	which spanned ConAgra Foods&#146; branded and private label businesses and was focused on the successful execution of business initiatives with U.S. retailers. Prior to this role, Mr.&nbsp;Booker served as Senior Vice President, Private Brand Sales
	from February 2013 to June 2014 at ConAgra Foods. In this role, Mr.&nbsp;Booker led the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	customer-facing
</FONT>
	integration of Ralcorp Holdings,&nbsp;Inc. following ConAgra Foods&#146; acquisition of the private
	brands business. From June 2010 to February 2013, Mr.&nbsp;Booker served as Vice President and General Manager, Frozen at ConAgra Foods. Prior to joining ConAgra Foods, Mr.&nbsp;Booker served as Vice President Sales, Laundry Care and Home Cleaning,
	at The Clorox Company, and also in field sales roles at Proctor&nbsp;&amp; Gamble. Mr.&nbsp;Booker holds a Bachelor of Science degree in Business Administration with a concentration in Marketing from California Polytechnic State University at San
	Luis Obispo.
</P>

</I>
</B>
	Tony Schroder became our President, Convenience in September 2010.
	In this role, Mr.&nbsp;Schroder oversees our convenience segment. Mr.&nbsp;Schroder joined us as a production supervisor in February 1991 and has served in various capacities prior to his current position. Mr.&nbsp;Schroder has served as our Senior
	Vice President of Sales and as a Group Vice President of Sales, Marketing and Product Development for the vending, convenience and warehouse retail divisions. Mr.&nbsp;Schroder has also worked within our other business segments in a variety of
	national and sales management positions. Mr.&nbsp;Schroder previously served on the board of directors of the National Automatic Merchandising Association (NAMA) and is a NAMA Certified Executive, a designation awarded to distinguished professionals
	in the field. Mr.&nbsp;Schroder holds a Bachelor of Arts degree in Business Management from Northern Kentucky University.

	Harson.

	was a partner at Thompson Hine&nbsp;LLP in the corporate transactions and securities practice group and acted as our outside general counsel. Ms.&nbsp;Harson joined Thompson Hine in 1996. Ms.&nbsp;Harson holds a bachelor&#146;s degree from The Ohio
	State University and a Juris Doctor degree from the University of Dayton School of Law. Ms.&nbsp;Harson currently serves as a member of the University of Dayton School of Law&#146;s advisory council.

<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">

	20&nbsp;years in various roles in research and development, manufacturing and quality assurance. Mr.&nbsp;Theis holds a Bachelor of Science degree in Chemical Engineering from University of Cincinnati.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Dean Hollis.
</I>
</B>
	Dean Hollis has served as our director since 2008. Mr.&nbsp;Hollis presently serves as a senior advisor for
	Oaktree. Prior to retiring in 2008, Mr.&nbsp;Hollis served as the President and Chief Operating Officer of the Consumer Foods Division of ConAgra Foods from December 2004 to July 2008. In that role, Mr.&nbsp;Hollis developed and executed a worldwide
	business transformation strategy, while overseeing the largest part of the ConAgra Foods portfolio. During Mr.&nbsp;Hollis&#146; 21&nbsp;years with ConAgra Foods, he held many executive level positions, including Executive Vice President, Retail
	Products; President, Grocery Foods; President, Frozen Foods; President, Specialty Foods; and President, Gilardi Foods. Mr.&nbsp;Hollis presently serves as Chairman of the board of directors of SunOpta Foods,&nbsp;Inc. and on the board of trustees at
	Stetson University. Mr.&nbsp;Hollis previously served on the board of directors of Diamond Foods,&nbsp;Inc., where he served on the audit and nominating and governance committees. Mr.&nbsp;Hollis also previously served on the board of directors of
	Boulder Brands,&nbsp;Inc., where he served as Chair of the board of directors and on the audit committee. Mr.&nbsp;Hollis also served on the board of directors of Landec Corporation, where he chaired the compensation committee. Dean has several
	privately held businesses and investments, ranging from transportation services, to specialized retail. Mr.&nbsp;Hollis is a graduate of Stetson University. Mr.&nbsp;Hollis also currently serves as Chair of the Board of Trustees of Brownell Talbot
	College Preparatory School.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Stephen A. Kaplan.
</I>
</B>
	Stephen A. Kaplan has served as our director since 2008. Mr.&nbsp;Kaplan is
	an Advisory Partner and a former Principal and head of Oaktree&#146;s Special Situations Group. He joined Oaktree in 1995, having previously served as a managing director of TCW and portfolio manager in the TCW Special Credits Group. Prior to
	joining TCW in 1993, Mr.&nbsp;Kaplan was a Partner with the law firm of Gibson, Dunn&nbsp;&amp; Crutcher. He presently serves on the boards of Regal Entertainment Group and Townsquare Media,&nbsp;Inc. Mr.&nbsp;Kaplan previously served on the boards
	of Oaktree Capital Group,&nbsp;LLC, Alliance HealthCare Services,&nbsp;Inc., Genco Shipping and Trading&nbsp;Ltd. and General Maritime Corporation. In addition, he currently serves on the boards of several private companies and nonprofit
	organizations, including the UCLA Jonsson Comprehensive Cancer Center Foundation and the New York University School of Law Foundation. Mr.&nbsp;Kaplan graduated with a B.S. degree in political science summa cum laude from the State University of New
	York at Stony Brook and a J.D. from the New York University School of Law.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Mr.&nbsp;Perlin also advised the U.S. Department of the Treasury as Special Government Employee from February 2014 to June 2014. Mr.&nbsp;Perlin currently serves on the board of directors of Abt
	Associates,&nbsp;Inc., where he serves as
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Non-Executive
</FONT>
	Chairman of the Board. Mr.&nbsp;Perlin also currently serves on the boards of State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Company, where he chairs the audit
	committee, and State Farm Bank, FSB, where he chairs the credit committee. Mr.&nbsp;Perlin previously served on the board of directors of Avolon Holdings,&nbsp;Ltd., where he chaired the audit committee and risk committee. Mr.&nbsp;Perlin was
	educated at the Georgetown University School of Foreign Service with a degree in International Affairs, the London School of Economics with an M.Sc. in Economics, and earned an M.P.A., Economics and Public Policy, from Princeton University&#146;s
	Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Matthew C. Wilson.
</I>
</B>
	Matthew C. Wilson has served as our director
	since 2008. Mr.&nbsp;Wilson is a Managing Director who has been with Oaktree since November 2007. He began serving as a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Co-Portfolio
</FONT>
	Manager within the Special Situations Group since 2014, and maintains
	responsibility for the U.S. Global Principal team and all of its investment activities. Mr.&nbsp;Wilson leads Oaktree&#146;s investing efforts in the consumer sector where he is responsible for sourcing, analyzing and executing transactions as well
	as monitoring portfolio companies in the food and beverage, retail/restaurant and consumer products sectors. Mr.&nbsp;Wilson worked at H.I.G. Capital,&nbsp;LLC from 2003 to 2007, where he was a founding member of Bayside Capital,&nbsp;Inc., a firm
	focused on special situations and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	credit-oriented
</FONT>
	investments. From 1999 to 2001, he worked at J.H. Whitney&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Co., in its middle market buyout group. Mr.&nbsp;Wilson began his career in the
	Investment Banking division at Merrill Lynch&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Co. where he worked from 1997 to 1999. He currently serves as Chairman of Agro Merchants Group,&nbsp;LLC and Quiksilver,&nbsp;Inc., and on the board of Glam Squad,&nbsp;Inc.
	Mr.&nbsp;Wilson previously served on the boards of Billabong International&nbsp;Ltd., Diamond Foods,&nbsp;Inc. and Bridge Direct,&nbsp;Inc. He is also Chairman of the Board of Trustees of The Children&#146;s Bureau of Los Angeles. Mr.&nbsp;Wilson
	earned a B.A. degree with distinction in economics and history from the University of Virginia and an M.B.A. from the Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Composition of our Board of Directors
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our business and affairs are managed under the direction of our board of directors. Our board of directors currently consists of eight
	directors. We have a classified board of directors, with two directors in Class&nbsp;I (Mr.&nbsp;Kaplan and Mr.&nbsp;Sliva), three directors in Class&nbsp;II (Mr.&nbsp;Dillingham, Mr.&nbsp;Simons and Mr.&nbsp;Hollis) and three directors in
	Class&nbsp;III (Dr.&nbsp;Clark, Mr.&nbsp;Wilson and Mr.&nbsp;Perlin). Any additional directorships resulting from an increase in the number of directors will be distributed among the three classes so that the number of directors in each class is
	nearly equal as possible. See &#147;Description of Capital
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Stock&#151;Anti-Takeover
</FONT>
	Effects of Our Amended and Restated Certificate of Incorporation and Amended and Restated Bylaws and Certain Provisions of
	Delaware Law&#151;Classified Board of Directors.&#148; In addition, we entered into a new stockholders agreement with our principal stockholders in connection with our initial public offering. This agreement grants Oaktree the right to designate
	nominees to our board of directors, subject to the maintenance of specified ownership requirements. See &#147;Certain Relationships and Related Party Transactions&#151;Stockholders Agreement.&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Under our amended and restated certificate of incorporation, our board of directors must consist of no fewer than five and no more than eleven
	directors, with the exact number of directors determined from time to time by resolution of our board of directors. Subject to the rights granted to one or more series of preferred stock then outstanding or the rights granted under the stockholders
	agreement with our principal stockholders, any newly created directorship or vacancies on our board of directors will be filled only by the affirmative vote of a majority of the remaining directors, although less than a quorum, by a sole remaining
	director or by the stockholders; provided, however, at any time when Oaktree and its affiliates beneficially own, in the aggregate, less than 40% in voting power of our stock entitled to vote generally in the election of directors, any newly created
	directorship on our board of directors that results from an increase in the number of directors and any vacancy occurring in our board of directors may only be filled by a majority of the directors then in office, although less than a quorum, or by
	a sole remaining director (and not by stockholders). Each director will hold office until the annual meeting of stockholders for the year in which his or her term expires and until his or her successor has been duly elected and qualified or until
	his or her earlier death, resignation, retirement, disqualification or removal.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	103
</P>

	Our board of directors has determined that Dr.&nbsp;Clark, Mr.&nbsp;Hollis and Mr.&nbsp;Perlin
	are independent as defined in the federal securities laws and the NYSE rules. We expect our board of directors to determine that Mr.&nbsp;Dillingham is independent in advance of our next annual meeting of stockholders.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Background and Experience of Directors
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	When considering whether directors and nominees have the experience, qualifications, attributes or skills, taken as a whole, to enable our
	board of directors to satisfy its oversight responsibilities effectively in light of our business and structure, our board of directors focused primarily on each person&#146;s background and experience as reflected in the information discussed in
	each of the directors&#146; individual biographies set forth above. We believe that our directors provide an appropriate mix of experience and skills relevant to the size and nature of our business. In particular, the members of our board of
	directors considered the following important characteristics, among others: (1)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Simons, our Chief Executive Officer, has extensive experience in the food industry through his leadership positions with agribusiness, food and consumer
	products companies; (2)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Sliva, our President, has extensive experience as a public food company executive; (3)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Kaplan and Mr.&nbsp;Wilson have significant financial, investment and operational experience from their
	involvement in Oaktree&#146;s investments in numerous portfolio companies and have played active roles in overseeing those businesses; (4) Dr.&nbsp;Clark has extensive experience with board governance, compliance and risk management, nutritional
	science and regulatory affairs; (5)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Dillingham has significant experience in the food industry; (6)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Hollis has significant executive level experience in the food industry and extensive experience with public companies;
	and (7)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Perlin has significant financial, business and public company experience. Our board of directors also considered how Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; role as our Chief Executive Officer and Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s role as our President
	would provide valuable information about the status of our
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	day-to-day
</FONT>
</FONT>
	operations and bring a management perspective to the deliberations of our board of directors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Board Leadership Structure
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our board of directors is led by Mr.&nbsp;Hollis, our
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Non-Executive
</FONT>
	Chairman. The Chief Executive
	Officer position is separate from the Chairman position. We believe that the separation of the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer positions is appropriate corporate governance for us at this time.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Role of Board in Risk Oversight
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our board of directors has extensive involvement in the oversight of risk management related to us and our business and accomplishes this
	oversight through the regular reporting by the Audit Committee. The Audit Committee represents our board of directors by periodically reviewing our accounting, reporting and financial practices, including the integrity of our financial statements,
	the surveillance of administrative and financial controls and our compliance with legal and regulatory requirements. Through its regular meetings with management, including the finance, legal and internal audit functions, the Audit Committee reviews
	and discusses all significant areas of our business and summarizes for our board of directors all areas of risk and the appropriate mitigating factors. In addition, our board of directors receives periodic detailed operating performance reviews from
	management.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Controlled Company Exception
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Because our principal stockholders currently control a majority of the voting power of our outstanding common stock, we are a &#147;controlled
	company&#148; within the meaning of the corporate governance standards of the NYSE. As a result, we are permitted, and have elected, not to comply with certain corporate governance standards, including (1)&nbsp;the requirement that a majority of the
	board of directors consist of independent directors, (2)&nbsp;the requirement that we have a compensation committee that is composed entirely of independent directors, and (3)&nbsp;the requirement that we have a nominating and corporate governance
	committee that is composed entirely of independent directors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	104
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage111"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Upon completion of this offering, our principal stockholders will no longer control a majority of
	the voting power of our outstanding common stock. As a result, we will no longer be a &#147;controlled company&#148; within the meaning of the NYSE. However, we will continue to qualify for, and may rely on, exemptions from certain corporate
	governance requirements that would otherwise provide protection to stockholders of other companies during a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	one-year
</FONT>
	transition period. The NYSE rules will require that we (1)&nbsp;have a board of directors
	that is composed of a majority of &#147;independent directors&#148; as defined under the rules of the NYSE within one year of the date we no longer qualify as a &#147;controlled company,&#148; (2)&nbsp;have a compensation committee that consists of
	a majority of independent directors within 90&nbsp;days of the date we no longer qualify as a &#147;controlled company&#148; and consists entirely of independent directors within one year of the date we no longer qualify as a &#147;controlled
	company,&#148; and (3)&nbsp;have a nominating and corporate governance committee that consists of a majority of independent directors within 90&nbsp;days of the date we no longer qualify as a &#147;controlled company,&#148; and consists entirely of
	independent directors within one year of the date we no longer qualify as a &#147;controlled company.&#148; During these transition periods, we may continue to utilize the available exemptions from certain corporate governance requirements, as
	permitted by the NYSE rules. Accordingly, you will not have the same protections afforded to stockholders of companies that are subject to all of the corporate governance requirements of the NYSE.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Board Committees
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The standing committees
	of our board of directors consist of an Audit Committee, a Compensation Committee and a Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our Chief Executive Officer and other executive officers regularly report to the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-executive
</FONT>
	directors and the Audit Committee, the Compensation Committee and the Nomination and Corporate Governance Committee to ensure effective and efficient oversight of our activities and to assist in proper risk management and the ongoing evaluation of
	management controls. We believe that the leadership structure of our board of directors provides appropriate risk oversight of our activities given the controlling interests held by our principal stockholders.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Audit Committee
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The members of our Audit Committee are Mr. Perlin (Interim Chairman), Dr. Clark and Mr.&nbsp;Wilson. Our board of directors has determined that
	Dr.&nbsp;Clark and Mr.&nbsp;Perlin qualify as independent directors under the corporate governance standards of the NYSE and the independence requirements of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Rule&nbsp;10A-3
</FONT>
	of the Exchange Act. We expect
	Mr.&nbsp;Wilson to resign from the Audit Committee within one year of the completion of our initial public offering so that all of our Audit Committee members will be independent as such term is defined in
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Rule&nbsp;10A-3(b)(i)
</FONT>
	under the Exchange Act and under the NYSE. Our board of directors has determined that each member of our Audit Committee qualifies as an &#147;audit committee financial expert&#148; as
	such term is defined in Item&nbsp;407(d)(5) of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Regulation&nbsp;S-K.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The purpose of the Audit
	Committee is to prepare the audit committee report required by the SEC to be included in our proxy statement and to assist our board of directors in overseeing and monitoring (1)&nbsp;the quality and integrity of our financial statements,
	(2)&nbsp;our compliance with legal and regulatory requirements, (3)&nbsp;our independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s qualifications and independence, (4)&nbsp;the performance of our internal audit function and (5)&nbsp;the performance
	of our independent registered public accounting firm.
</P>

	The written charter for the Audit Committee is available on our website. The
	information contained on or accessible through our corporate website or any other website that we may maintain is not part of this prospectus or the registration statement of which this prospectus is a part.

	relating to (1)&nbsp;identifying individuals qualified to become new board members, consistent with criteria approved by our board of directors, (2)&nbsp;reviewing the qualifications of incumbent directors to determine whether to recommend them for
	reelection and selecting, or recommending that our board of directors select, the director nominees for the next annual meeting of stockholders, (3)&nbsp;identifying board members qualified to fill vacancies on any board committee and recommending
	that our board of directors appoint the identified member or members to the applicable committee, (4)&nbsp;reviewing and recommending to our board of directors corporate governance guidelines applicable to us, (5)&nbsp;overseeing the evaluation of
	our board of directors and management and (6)&nbsp;handling such other matters that are specifically delegated to the committee by our board of directors from time to time.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Compensation Discussion and Analysis
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Compensation Program Objectives and Design
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our compensation program for our executive officers (including our &#147;named executive officers&#148; identified in the Summary Compensation
	table) is designed to (1)&nbsp;attract and retain top talent; (2)&nbsp;motivate and reward the
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	106
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage113"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	performance of senior executives in support of achievement of strategic, financial, and operating performance objectives; and (3)&nbsp;align our executives&#146; interests with our investors. In
	order to achieve these goals, we target total direct compensation (which consists of base salary, target annual cash incentive compensation and target
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	long-term
</FONT>
	equity incentive awards) for our executive
	officers at the 50
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	th
</SUP>
	&nbsp;percentile of our identified peer group of companies, as discussed below. In doing so, we weight overall total direct compensation towards longer term incentives which
	aligns our executives&#146; compensation with our investors&#146; interests. To encourage pay for performance, we place a meaningful emphasis on variable versus fixed pay for our executive officers through the grant of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	long-term
</FONT>
	equity based compensation. This provides our executive officers a reward for achieving exceptional business results, while encouraging our executives to think and act like owners aligned with
	stockholders.
</P>
</EFX_COMMITTEE_INTERLOCKS>
</EFX_MANAGEMENT>
<EFX_EXECUTIVE_COMPENSATION>
<A NAME="FIS_EXECUTIVE_COMPENSATION"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Role of our Compensation Committee in Setting Executive Compensation
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our Compensation Committee has overall responsibility for determining the compensation of our executive officers. Members of our Compensation
	Committee are appointed by our board of directors. Our Compensation Committee consists of Mr.&nbsp;Perlin (Chairman), Mr.&nbsp;Dillingham, Mr.&nbsp;Hollis and Mr.&nbsp;Wilson, each of whom qualify as an &#147;outside director&#148; under
	Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended (the &#147;Code&#148;). See the section entitled &#147;Management&#151;Board Committees&#151;Compensation Committee.&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Role of Compensation Consultant
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our Compensation Committee has the authority to engage the services of outside consultants to assist it in making decisions regarding the
	establishment of our compensation programs and philosophy. Our Compensation Committee has retained Board Advisory as its compensation consultant to advise it in matters related to executive officers, including the design of our executive
	compensation program.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Role of Executive Officers in Compensation Decisions
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For executive officers other than our Chief Executive Officer and President, our Compensation Committee seeks and considers input from our
	Chief Executive Officer and our President regarding such executive officers&#146; responsibilities, performance and compensation. Specifically, our Chief Executive Officer and President recommend base salaries and equity award levels that are used
	in our compensation program, and advise our Compensation Committee regarding the compensation program&#146;s ability to attract, retain and motivate executive talent. These recommendations reflect compensation levels that our Chief Executive Officer
	and President believe are qualitatively commensurate with an executive officer&#146;s individual qualifications, experience, responsibility level, functional role, knowledge, skills and individual performance, as well as our performance. Our
	Compensation Committee considers our Chief Executive Officer&#146;s and President&#146;s recommendations, but may adjust up or down as it determines in its discretion, and approves the specific compensation for all the executive officers. Our
	Compensation Committee also relies on the experience of its members in determining and approving the specific compensation amounts. All such compensation determinations are largely discretionary.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Elements of Compensation
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The components of compensation for our named executive officers are:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Base salary;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

</TD>

	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;

<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Cash incentive compensation in the form of annual performance bonus (also called our Management Incentive Plan);
</TD>

</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">

<A NAME="eolPage114"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In general, we target total direct compensation for our executive officers as approximately 30%
	toward base salary; 20% toward annual performance bonus compensation and 50% toward
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	long-term
</FONT>
	equity compensation awards. We believe this creates an appropriate allocation of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	short-term
</FONT>
	and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	long-term
</FONT>
	incentives to ensure executive officers are properly balancing the need for consistent annual performance with the need for consistent
	performance over a multiple year horizon. In addition, this allocation of compensation is intended to ensure that our executive officers share in both downside risk and upside opportunity based on our performance.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Base Salary
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Base
	salaries are intended to compensate our named executive officers and all other salaried employees for their basic services performed for us on an annual basis. In setting base salaries, we take into account the employee&#146;s experience, the
	functions and responsibilities of the positions, salaries for similar positions within our peer group and for competitive positions in the food industry generally and any other factor relevant to that particular job. We generally aim to pay at the
	50
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	th
</SUP>
	&nbsp;percentile of our peer group for each position, but do not confine ourselves to this practice if other factors, such as experience, warrant a lower or higher base salary. Base salaries
	may be adjusted from time to time based on a named executive officer&#146;s performance or changes in job responsibilities, or may be supplemented by increased annual bonus or
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	long-term
</FONT>
	incentive compensation
	opportunities as determined appropriate by our Compensation Committee. Our Chief Executive Officer and our President recommend to our Compensation Committee the base salaries for their direct reports. Our Chief Executive Officer&#146;s and
	President&#146;s base salaries are set by our Compensation Committee, and are approved by our board of directors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Cash Incentive
	Compensation
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	APF maintains four
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	incentive-based
</FONT>
	compensation plans designed to provide
	&#147;pay for performance&#148; for our employees: the Management Incentive Plan, the Sales Incentive Plan, the Gainsharing Plan and the Profit Sharing Plan. All of our named executive officers participate in the Management Incentive Plan. For 2016,
	the Management Incentive Plan was structured as follows:
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_42"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">

	2016 Management Incentive Plan
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

	Metrics
</B>

	$265&nbsp;million EBITDA
</P>

</TABLE>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Payouts under the Management Incentive Plan are based on fiscal (calendar) year performance, and are scheduled
	to be made in February of each year for the prior fiscal year. Employees must remain on the payroll until the respective plan payment dates to remain eligible for a payout. Generally, new hires in January or February are eligible for full
	12&nbsp;months of bonus consideration; associates hired between March&nbsp;1 and September&nbsp;30 are eligible for a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pro-rated
</FONT>
	bonus in that fiscal year; associates hired between October&nbsp;1 and
	December&nbsp;31 are not eligible for bonus participation until the following full fiscal year. Our Compensation Committee evaluates our named executive officers&#146; achievement of specific performance goals with strong emphasis on their
	contributions to overall company performance in addition to their individual function. Bonus amounts are determined based on our Compensation Committee&#146;s assessment of a number of quantitative and qualitative factors. The target performance
	levels are challenging but achievable with strong performance, whereas the maximum performance levels represent stretch goals. Based on the funding level, awards are modified by an individual performance factor. The individual performance factor is
	based on an individual&#146;s performance review rating and can vary from zero percent (0%) of the funding level for failing to meet expectations to up to one hundred thirty percent (130%), and beyond in extraordinary situations, of the funding
	level for exceeding all performance expectations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	108
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage115"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Equity Compensation under our 2009 Omnibus Equity Incentive Plan
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our 2009 Omnibus Equity Incentive Plan (our &#147;2009 Plan&#148;) allows for the following types of equity awards: stock options, share
	appreciation rights, restricted shares (also known as restricted stock), deferred shares (or restricted share units), performance shares and other
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	share-based
</FONT>
	awards. Our employees, directors and consultants
	constitute eligible participants under the terms of our 2009 Plan. Under our 2009 Plan, we provide our employees and directors with equity compensation to further align management&#146;s interests with those of our stockholders. We intend that the
	prospective value of our annual
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	long-term
</FONT>
	equity compensation awards will be comprised of 50% stock options and 50% restricted share units, although this allocation may be adjusted to reflect peer company
	practices, the inclusion of restricted share awards and the potential introduction of performance share awards.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our Compensation
	Committee considers it in the best interests of our stockholders to encourage the continued attention and dedication of our senior executive officers to their assigned duties without distraction in the event of a change in control. Therefore, in the
	event of a &#147;Change in Control&#148; of the company, the vesting of a portion of equity grants under our 2009 Plan will accelerate and such grants will become immediately vested pursuant to the award agreements thereunder. See &#147;Potential
	Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control&#148; below for additional information.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Peer Company Analysis
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For purposes of designing and setting compensation levels for our executive officers, in fiscal 2016 our Compensation Committee, with the
	advice of its retained consultant, has designated a peer group of companies for comparison purposes. While our Compensation Committee intends to regularly review and make adjustments to this peer group of companies, the peer group for purposes of
	designing our executive compensation program is currently comprised of the following companies: B&amp;G Foods; Flowers Foods; J&nbsp;&amp; J Snack Foods; Lancaster Colony; Pinnacle Foods; Post Holdings; Sanderson Farms;
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Snyder&#146;s-Lance
</FONT>
	and TreeHouse Foods. These companies represent competitive peers with
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	last-fiscal
</FONT>
	year revenues ranging from approximately $960&nbsp;million to
	$5.0&nbsp;billion, with market capitalizations ranging from $2.1&nbsp;billion to $6.0&nbsp;billion.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Post-termination
</FONT>
	Severance Payments
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For the reasons stated in &#147;Equity Compensation under our 2009 Omnibus Equity Incentive Plan,&#148; we provide all of our named executive
	officers with
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	post-termination
</FONT>
	severance payments in the event of either termination by us without &#147;Cause&#148; or termination by an executive under limited circumstances in connection with a change in
	control. In fiscal 2016 we adopted the AdvancePierre Foods,&nbsp;Inc. 2016 Executive Severance Plan (the &#147;Executive Severance Plan&#148;), a cash severance plan pursuant to which each of our executive officers is entitled to cash severance and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Company-paid
</FONT>
	COBRA coverage upon a qualifying termination, subject to the terms thereof. Under the Executive Severance Plan, each of our executive officers is entitled to the better of cash severance which may be
	payable to them under their employment agreements with APF or the following multiples of base salary and the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	two-year
</FONT>
	average of prior years&#146; bonuses: two times for our Chief Executive Officer, one and a
	half times for our Chief Financial Officer and one times for other executive officers. See also &#147;Employment Agreements&#148; and &#147;Other Change of Control and Severance Agreements&#148; for additional information.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	109
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Benefit Plan Participation: 401(k) Plan and Other Benefits
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We provide various other benefits and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	compensation-related
</FONT>
	programs to our named executive officers and
	other employees, which allow us to provide a full and comprehensive compensation package. This full package of compensation elements is important to our objectives to attract, retain and incent
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	high-quality
</FONT>
	employees. The elements of our compensation program not otherwise discussed above are:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	A 401(k) plan in which we match up to 100% of the participant deferrals up to 3% of the participant&#146;s compensation, plus 50% of the amount of the participant&#146;s deferrals between 3% and 5% of the
	participant&#146;s compensation, up to a maximum company contribution of 4% of the employee&#146;s pay (up to the Internal Revenue Code annual covered compensation limit);
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

	&#149;
</TD>

	&nbsp;
</TD>

	Medical and dental insurance for which we pay approximately 75% of the premiums;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Long-Term
</FONT>
	Disability benefit which is a voluntary benefit for general employees (employee paid). For named executives, the benefit is paid for by us. Additionally, we provide a
	supplemental
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Long-Term
</FONT>
	Disability benefit to our named executives.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In establishing
	and providing the plans noted above, we use outside benefits consultants for 401(k), medical, dental and other employee benefits plan design. Each of the outside consultants provides advice not less than annually about the plan designs for similar
	manufacturing companies across the United States. As with other elements of compensation, we strive to provide competitive benefits to attract high quality executives. We believe that the benefits noted in this section generally are competitive with
	all similarly situated manufacturers and competitors with exceptions made where we believe necessary based on the communities where we are located.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We do not sponsor a defined benefit pension plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Share Ownership Guidelines
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In the interest of good corporate governance and to further align the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	long-term
</FONT>
	interests of our
	executives with our investors, our Compensation Committee has adopted guidelines setting forth target stock ownership levels of six times total annual base salary for our Chief Executive Officer, six times total annual base salary for our President,
	three times total annual base salary for our Chief Financial Officer and one times total annual base salary for our other officers. Our executive officers have five years within which to achieve the guidelines, although the guidelines have been
	achieved by all of our executive officers as of this offering.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	110
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage117"></A>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Narrative Disclosure to Summary Compensation Table and Grants of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Plan-Based
</FONT>
	Awards in Fiscal Year 2016
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Employment Agreements
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	John N. Simons, Jr. (Chief Executive Officer).
</I>
</B>
	APF entered into an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Simons effective as of
	September&nbsp;30, 2013. Pursuant to his employment agreement, Mr.&nbsp;Simons is entitled to a base salary of $550,000, which APF increased to $675,000 in 2016, and an annual bonus ranging from 0% to 200% of his base salary, with the board of
	directors historically setting the target amount at 100% of base salary, determined according to overall company EBITDA. Mr.&nbsp;Simons received an equity award in connection with entry into his employment agreement and became eligible to
	participate in our 401(k) plan, health insurance,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	short-term
</FONT>
	and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	long-term
</FONT>
	disability insurance, life insurance and other employee benefit plans with the terms and
	conditions of those plans, as may be amended from time to time. Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; employment agreement contains benefits to be paid in the event of resignation for &#147;Good Reason&#148; (as defined below) or termination by APF for reasons
	other than &#147;Cause&#148; (as defined below), death or disability. Under such circumstances and contingent upon Mr.&nbsp;Simons signing and not revoking a comprehensive release of claims substantially in a form provided by APF, Mr.&nbsp;Simons
	would receive: (1)&nbsp;a severance payment equal to 1.5 times his
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	then-current
</FONT>
	base salary; plus (2)&nbsp;1.5 times the average of the two annual bonuses paid to him with respect to the immediately preceding
	two years (or, if such termination occurs after the first complete year but before the second complete year following his commencement of employment, 1.5 times the average of the actual bonus paid with respect to the first full fiscal year
	commencing with his employment and the bonus that would have been paid for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	then-current
</FONT>
	fiscal year had performance been met at the 100% achievement level); plus (3)&nbsp;COBRA continuation coverage until
	the earlier of (a)&nbsp;18&nbsp;months following the date of his termination of employment or (b)&nbsp;the date on which he obtains other medical plan coverage, whether from another employer or elsewhere. Also under the terms of
	Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; employment agreement, upon the occurrence of any &#147;Change in Control&#148; (as defined below), his outstanding equity, annual bonus and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	long-term
</FONT>
	incentive awards will immediately
	vest (and not be subject to forfeiture for any reason) in a manner to enable him to fully participate in such Change in Control transaction and, to the extent any vested options granted on or after the effective date of his employment agreement
	survive such Change in Control, will remain vested and exercisable in accordance with their original terms (including in connection with a termination of his employment with APF).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For purposes of Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; employment agreement,
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

</TD>

	&#149;
</TD>

	&nbsp;

	&#147;Cause&#148; means the conviction or commission of or the entry of a guilty plea or plea of no contest to any felony or to any other crime involving moral turpitude.

	merger or consolidation or sale or other disposition of all or substantially all of our assets, unless following such business transaction (a)&nbsp;all or substantially all of the individuals and
	entities who were the beneficial owners of the outstanding equity interest and outstanding voting securities immediately prior to such business transaction beneficially own, directly or indirectly, 50% or more of, respectively, the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	then-outstanding
</FONT>
	shares of common stock and the combined voting power of the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	then-outstanding
</FONT>
	voting securities entitled to vote generally in the election of directors, as the
	case may be, of the entity resulting from the business transaction in substantially the same proportion as their ownership immediately prior to such business transaction; and (b)&nbsp;at least a majority of the members of the board of directors of
	the corporation resulting from such business transaction were members of the incumbent board at the time of the execution of the initial agreement, or of the action of the board of directors, providing for such business transaction; or (4)&nbsp;the
	approval by our stockholders of a complete liquidation or dissolution of us.

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	&#147;Good Reason&#148; means the occurrence of any of the following events, if Mr.&nbsp;Simons provides APF with adequate notice as provided in his agreement: (1)&nbsp;a diminution in Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; base salary
	or target bonus, except for any reduction not to exceed 10% of his salary or target bonus if such reduction is applicable to all executive officers; (2)&nbsp;the failure to pay any compensation required under the terms of his employment agreement;
	(3)&nbsp;a material diminution in Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; authority, duties or responsibilities; (4)&nbsp;a relocation of Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; primary business office by greater than 50 miles from such office as of the effective date of his
	employment agreement; (5)&nbsp;a requirement that Mr.&nbsp;Simons report to a person or entity other than the board of either APF or us; or (6)&nbsp;any other action or inaction that constitutes a material breach by APF of Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146;
	employment agreement (as it may be amended from time to time).
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In connection with Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; anticipated
	retirement and appointment of a successor Chief Executive Officer and President, on October&nbsp;26, 2016, Mr.&nbsp;Simons agreed to waive his right to terminate his employment for Good Reason (as defined in his employment agreement) and receive
	severance payments and benefits following such termination pursuant to his employment agreement by reason of his resignation from the positions of President and Chief Executive Officer at such time as his successor is appointed to such positions
	pursuant to a waiver agreement with APF.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On November&nbsp;7, 2016, we and APF entered into a transition and separation agreement with
	Mr.&nbsp;Simons, pursuant to which Mr.&nbsp;Simons will resign from his employment with us effective March&nbsp;31, 2017 and from his service on our board of directors effective as of the date of the 2017 annual meeting of our stockholders. The
	transition and separation agreement supersedes and replaces Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; employment agreement. Pursuant to the transition and separation agreement, during the period commencing on November&nbsp;7, 2016 and ending on March&nbsp;31, 2017,
	Mr.&nbsp;Simons will remain employed by APF and continue to perform his duties and responsibilities and assist in connection with the transition of his duties to his successor, Mr.&nbsp;Sliva. During this period, Mr.&nbsp;Simons will continue to be
	paid his current annual base salary and receive payment of his annual incentive bonus for fiscal 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On March&nbsp;31, 2017 (or, if
	earlier, upon the termination of Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; employment by APF without &#147;Cause&#148; (as defined in his employment agreement) or by Mr.&nbsp;Simons for &#147;Good Reason&#148; (as defined in his employment agreement and subject to the
	terms of the waiver agreement) or by reason of his death or disability), and subject to his execution and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-revocation
</FONT>
	of a general release of claims, Mr.&nbsp;Simons (or his estate) will receive the
	following severance payments and benefits:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

	Continued health insurance benefits at our expense until the earlier of 18&nbsp;months following March&nbsp;31, 2017 (or such earlier date of termination), or the date on which he obtains other medical plan coverage.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Christopher D. Sliva (President)
</I>
</B>
	On October&nbsp;27, 2016, we and APF entered into an employment agreement
	with Mr.&nbsp;Sliva that sets forth the terms of his employment, which commenced on November&nbsp;14, 2016. Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s employment agreement has a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	three-year
</FONT>
	term commencing on November&nbsp;14, 2016
	and ending on November&nbsp;14, 2019, unless earlier terminated. The agreement automatically renews for
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	one-year
</FONT>
	periods unless terminated by either party on not less than 180 days&#146; notice. Under the
	terms of his employment agreement, Mr.&nbsp;Sliva will receive an annual base salary of $800,000, subject to increase in the discretion of our board of directors. Commencing with fiscal 2017, Mr.&nbsp;Sliva will be eligible for an annual incentive
	bonus which is payable upon the satisfaction of certain performance targets established by our board of directors after consultation with Mr.&nbsp;Sliva. Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s target annual bonus will be 100% of his annual base salary and the
	maximum annual bonus will be 200% of his annual base salary. In addition, Mr.&nbsp;Sliva received a signing bonus of $325,000 in November 2016, which is repayable by Mr.&nbsp;Sliva if his employment is terminated due to his resignation other than
	for &#147;Good Reason&#148; or due to his &#147;disability&#148; or by us for &#147;Cause&#148; (each as defined in his employment agreement) at any time prior to November&nbsp;14, 2017. In connection with Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s relocation to the
	Ohio area, we will pay up to $272,000, which is repayable by Mr.&nbsp;Sliva if his employment is terminated due to his resignation other than for Good Reason or due to his disability or by us for Cause at any time prior to November&nbsp;14, 2017, in
	addition to providing reimbursement for certain moving expenses up to $30,000.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Pursuant to his employment agreement and under our 2009
	Plan, on November&nbsp;14, 2016, we granted Mr.&nbsp;Sliva a number of shares of our common stock having a grant date value of $325,011. Mr.&nbsp;Sliva is prohibited from selling or otherwise transferring such shares at any time prior to
	November&nbsp;14, 2017. Such shares are returnable by Mr.&nbsp;Sliva (or his executor, as the case may be) if his employment is terminated by us for Cause or by him without Good Reason or due to his death or disability at any time prior to
	November&nbsp;14, 2017. In addition, on November&nbsp;14, 2016, we granted Mr.&nbsp;Sliva a number of restricted stock units under our 2009 Plan having a grant date value of $5,000,006 (the &#147;Replacement Grant&#148;), which will vest in
	substantially equal installments on each of the first four anniversaries of November&nbsp;14, 2016, subject to accelerated vesting upon a qualifying termination of employment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Commencing with our 2017 fiscal year, Mr.&nbsp;Sliva will be eligible to receive an annual equity award grant with respect to each full fiscal
	year pursuant to our 2009 Plan, comprised of 50% restricted stock units and 50% stock options as determined by our board of directors, having a grant date value of $2,250,000, which will vest in substantially equal installments on each of the first
	four anniversaries of the grant date, and which are otherwise subject to the same terms and conditions that apply to annual equity awards granted to our other senior executives.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	If, during the term of his employment agreement, Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s employment is terminated by us without Cause or by him for Good Reason,
	in either case, prior to a Change in Control of us, and subject to his execution and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-revocation
</FONT>
	of a general release of claims and continued compliance with the restrictive covenants set forth in his
	employment agreement (as described below), he will receive the following severance payments and benefits:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

</FONT>

	to him for the two fiscal years immediately preceding the date of termination (or if such termination occurs prior to the end of the first full fiscal year or second full fiscal year, respectively, the amount of the target annual bonus(es) for such
	fiscal year(s)), payable in substantially equal installments during the

<I>
	Michael B. Sims (Chief Financial Officer).

	APF entered into an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Sims on February&nbsp;2, 2012.
	Pursuant to his employment agreement, Mr.&nbsp;Sims is entitled to a base salary of $400,000, which APF increased to $420,000 in 2014 and $450,000 in 2016, and an annual bonus pursuant to the Management Incentive Plan with a target of 75% of his
	base salary and actual payout determined according to performance targets established by us. Mr.&nbsp;Sims received an equity award in connection with entry into his employment agreement and became eligible to participate in our 401(k) plan, health
	insurance,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	short-term
</FONT>
	and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	long-term
</FONT>
	disability insurance, life insurance and other employee benefit plans with the terms and conditions of those plans, as may be amended
	from time to time. Mr.&nbsp;Sims&#146; employment agreement contains benefits to be paid in connection with his termination (1)&nbsp;by APF for any reason other than &#147;Cause&#148; or by disability that continues for greater than 6&nbsp;months;
	or (2)&nbsp;by him within 3&nbsp;months following a &#147;Change in Control&#148; as a result of (a)&nbsp;a material reduction in his
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	then-current
</FONT>
	base salary or bonus level; (b)&nbsp;a change in office
	location requiring a relocation from the state of Ohio or in excess of 100 miles; (c)&nbsp;a change resulting in the material diminution of his
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	then-current
</FONT>
	job description and responsibilities; or (d)&nbsp;a
	material change in reporting relationship (in each case, provided he adhere to certain notice requirements). Under such circumstances and contingent upon Mr.&nbsp;Sims signing and not revoking a comprehensive release of claims substantially in a
	form provided by us, Mr.&nbsp;Sims would receive salary continuation payments for 12&nbsp;months (which payments would reduce any severance due to him under any other company severance plan, program or arrangement).
</P>

	APF entered into an employment agreement with
	Mr.&nbsp;Clough effective as of June&nbsp;18, 2013. Pursuant to his employment agreement, Mr.&nbsp;Clough is entitled to a base salary of $385,000, which APF increased to $450,000 in 2016, and an annual bonus pursuant to the Management Incentive

	that continues for greater than 6&nbsp;months; or (2)&nbsp;by him within 3&nbsp;months following a &#147;Change in Control&#148; as a result of (a)&nbsp;a material reduction in his
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">

<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">

	would reduce any severance due to him under any other company severance plan, program or arrangement). On March&nbsp;24, 2016, Mr.&nbsp;Clough and APF entered into an amendment to Mr.&nbsp;Clough&#146;s employment agreement. The amendment contains a
	contingent payment feature stating that if Mr.&nbsp;Clough voluntarily terminates employment with APF prior to the three year anniversary of October&nbsp;14, 2014, the date on which APF loaned Mr.&nbsp;Clough $100,000 to facilitate his physical
	relocation on short notice in furtherance of his service to APF, or is terminated for Cause (as defined in his employment agreement) prior to such date, Mr.&nbsp;Clough will pay APF $100,000. The amendment contains a partial payment acceleration
	feature in the event of certain company liquidity transactions.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Other Change of Control and Severance Agreements
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We maintain a standard severance policy and a Special Enhanced Severance Plan. None of our named executive officers participate in either plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We also maintain the Executive Severance Plan, which we adopted on July&nbsp;20, 2016, and is intended to provide benefits to our Chief
	Executive Officer, Chief Financial Officer and certain other executive officers in the event of the executive officers&#146; termination of employment without Cause (as defined below) by APF and the executive officer does not receive superior
	benefits in their individual employment agreements. For purposes of the Executive Severance Plan, &#147;Cause&#148; means (a)&nbsp;if an executive officer is party to a written employment agreement with APF, the meaning ascribed to such term therein
	(if any); (b)&nbsp;if an executive officer is not party to&nbsp;a written employment agreement with APF or such written employment agreement ascribes no meaning to such term, then if such executive officer is party to the Special Enhanced Severance
	Plan, the meaning ascribed to such term therein; or (c)&nbsp;if an executive officer is not party to a written employment agreement with APF or such written employment agreement ascribes no meaning to such term and if an executive officer is not
	party to
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	116

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	the Special Enhanced Severance Plan, then a termination of an executive officer&#146;s employment because of an executive officer&#146;s (i)&nbsp;material breach of a written employment contract
	with APF; (ii)&nbsp;willful violation of any law, rule or regulation, which violation results, or could reasonably be expected to result, in material harm to the business or reputation of APF; (iii)&nbsp;conviction or commission of, or the entry of
	a guilty plea or plea of no contest to, any felony or other crime involving moral turpitude; or (iv)&nbsp;disclosure of confidential information regarding APF or its business. The definition of &#147;Cause&#148; may also include a termination of an
	executive officer&#146;s employment because of an executive officer&#146;s (i)&nbsp;failure to perform his or her duties to APF; (ii)&nbsp;violation of any material policy of APF (including, but not limited to, the covenants set forth in the
	Executive Severance Plan); or (iii)&nbsp;misappropriation, embezzlement or dishonesty. The Executive Severance Plan&#146;s benefits are as follows:
</P>

	the grant date fair value of these awards are set forth in &#147;Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations&#151;Critical Accounting Policies and

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following table provides potential payments that may be made to each named executive officer upon termination and/or a change in control as
	defined and pursuant to each executive&#146;s executive employment agreement or, if the Executive Severance Plan provides for greater cash severance benefits than such agreement, then in lieu of such agreement, the Executive Severance Plan. In order
	to receive severance benefits under their respective employment agreements, each of our named executive officers must sign and timely return, and not revoke, a comprehensive release of claims and demonstrate continued compliance with the
	confidentiality,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-compete,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-solicitation
</FONT>
	and/or
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-interference
</FONT>
	provisions of his employment agreement, as applicable.
	None of our named executive officers participate in the Special Enhanced Severance Plan. The amounts shown in the table below assume that the executive was terminated on December&nbsp;31, 2016 and that the effective date of the change in control was
	December&nbsp;31, 2016, and do not include amounts (if any) in which the named executive officer had already vested as of December&nbsp;31, 2016. The amounts shown below are hypothetical payments calculated using the assumptions required under
	applicable regulations, and do not represent actual payments to any named executive officer. The actual compensation to be paid can only be determined at the time of a named executive officer&#146;s termination of employment or upon a change in
	control, as applicable.
</P>

	The amounts in this table reflect the payments that Mr.&nbsp;Simons would have received had his employment been terminated on December&nbsp;31, 2016 pursuant to his transition and separation agreement, dated
	November&nbsp;7, 2016, which superseded and replaced his employment agreement (except with respect to certain employment agreement provisions, including the change in control provisions, which survive), and pursuant to our 2009 Plan. If instead
	Mr.&nbsp;Simons resigns from his employment with us effective March&nbsp;31, 2017, then in lieu of the payments quantified in this table and assuming Mr.&nbsp;Simons has no outstanding (i.e., earned but unpaid) annual bonus with respect to fiscal
	2016 as of such date, Mr.&nbsp;Simons would be entitled to accelerated vesting with respect to 61,856 restricted share units and 185,567 option shares (granted on August&nbsp;26, 2016 with an exercise price of $25.69 per share) (the &#147;Simons
	Equity Acceleration&#148;) and payment by us of COBRA premiums with respect to health and welfare plan coverage for Mr.&nbsp;Simons (and his dependents, if covered under such plan as of the date of termination) for 18 months ($18,134) (the
	&#147;Simons COBRA Continuation&#148;).

</TR>
