<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(2)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Reflects the Simons Equity Acceleration pursuant to the terms of the applicable award agreements and Section&nbsp;10 of his employment agreement, which survives the termination of such agreement, as set forth in
	Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; transition and separation agreement.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(3)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Reflects: (a)&nbsp;a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	lump-sum
</FONT>
	payment equal to any unpaid annual bonus earned by Mr.&nbsp;Simons for fiscal 2016, calculated at his 2015 level because his 2016 bonus amount has
	not yet been determined; (b)&nbsp;the Simons Equity Acceleration pursuant to Section 3(b) of his transition and separation agreement; and (c)&nbsp;the Simons COBRA Continuation, in each case pursuant to his transition and separation agreement. These
	benefits would apply in lieu of the 2016 Executive Severance Plan pursuant to Mr.&nbsp;Simons&#146; transition and separation agreement.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

	&nbsp;

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(1)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Reflects accelerated vesting pursuant to the terms of the applicable award agreements (and, with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s restricted stock units, his employment agreement) with respect to 12,671 restricted
	shares and 194,932 restricted share units, in each case valued at $29.78 per share, which was our closing price on December&nbsp;30, 2016 (the &#147;Sliva Equity Acceleration&#148;).
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(2)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Reflects (a)&nbsp;a lump sum payment equal to the sum of (i)&nbsp;three times Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s then-current annual base salary ($800,000) plus (ii)&nbsp;three times Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s target annual bonus for
	2016 ($800,000); (b) continued health insurance benefits at our expense for 18 months following the date of termination ($26,001) (the &#147;Sliva COBRA Continuation&#148;); and (c)&nbsp;the Sliva Equity Acceleration pursuant to the terms of the
	applicable award agreements (and, with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s restricted stock units, his employment agreement).
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(3)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Reflects: (a)&nbsp;a payment equal to the sum of (i)&nbsp;two times Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s annual base salary ($800,000), plus (ii)&nbsp;two times Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s target annual bonus for 2016 ($800,000) payable in
	substantially equal installments during the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	two-year
</FONT>
	period commencing on the date of termination; (b)&nbsp;the Sliva COBRA Continuation; and (c)&nbsp;the Sliva Equity Acceleration pursuant to the terms of the
	applicable award agreements (and, with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s restricted stock units, his employment agreement). Mr.&nbsp;Sliva would receive no additional benefit under the 2016 Executive Severance Plan upon a termination without Cause
	because the 2016 Executive Severance Plan does not provide for greater benefits than Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s employment agreement.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(4)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Reflects the Sliva Equity Acceleration pursuant to the terms of the applicable award agreements (and, with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Sliva&#146;s restricted stock units, his employment agreement).
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">

	Reflects accelerated vesting pursuant to the terms of the applicable award agreements, in each case valued at $29.78 per share, which was our closing price on December&nbsp;30, 2016 as follows: (a)&nbsp;with respect to
	Mr.&nbsp;Sims, 90,344 restricted share units and 37,113 option shares; (b)&nbsp;with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle, 16,437 restricted shares, 90,344 restricted share units and 37,113 option shares; and (c)&nbsp;with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Clough,
	90,344 restricted share units and 37,113 option shares.

	(2)

	Reflects payments under the 2016 Executive Severance Plan as follows: (a)&nbsp;with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Sims, one and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	one-half
</FONT>
	times the sum of base salary ($450,000) and the two
	year average of prior years&#146; bonuses (for 2014, $105,000, and for 2015, $410,000) and 18 months of COBRA continuation; (b)&nbsp;with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle, one times the sum of base salary ($450,000 and the two year average of prior
	years&#146; bonuses (for 2014, $156,250, and for 2015, $400,000) and 12 months of COBRA continuation; and (c)&nbsp;with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Clough, one times the sum of base salary ($450,000) and the two year average of prior years&#146; bonuses
	(for 2014, $146,250, and for 2015, $360,000) and 12 months of COBRA continuation.
</TD>

	(3)
</TD>

	Reflects 12 months of salary continuation payments pursuant to each applicable employment agreement and eight weeks of COBRA continuation payments pursuant to our standard severance policy (which COBRA payments would be
	payable regardless of whether such termination occurred within 3 months after a Change in Control).

<A NAME="FIS_DIRECTOR_COMPENSATION"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Compensation of Directors
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Directors who are also executive officers do not receive any additional compensation for serving as members of our board of directors or any
	committee of our board of directors. Each
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-employee
</FONT>
	director is eligible for reimbursement for his or her expenses incurred in connection with attendance at our board of directors meetings in accordance
	with our policy. Additionally,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-employee
</FONT>
	directors are compensated as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Annual
	Cash Retainers.
</I>
</B>
	Following our initial public offering, our board of directors adopted a director compensation policy, pursuant to which each
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-employee
</FONT>
	director receives the following:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	an annual grant of $120,000 in restricted stock units, which vest
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	one-third
</FONT>
	per year over a three year period;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

	The cash retainers are paid in equal quarterly installments, and each director may elect to receive restricted stock units in lieu of cash
	subject to the terms of our policy. Restricted stock units accrue dividend equivalents at the same rate and at the same times as cash dividends are paid on shares of our common stock, and directors may elect to defer commencement of the settlement
	of restricted stock units pursuant to the terms thereof in compliance with the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the Code.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<A NAME="D304963DS1A_HTM_ROM304963_16">
</A>
	PRINCIPAL AND SELLING STOCKHOLDERS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following table sets forth information with respect to the beneficial ownership of our common stock by (1)&nbsp;each individual or entity
	known by us to beneficially own more than 5% of our outstanding common stock, (2)&nbsp;each of our named executive officers, (3)&nbsp;each of our directors, (4)&nbsp;all of our directors and our executive officers as a group and (5)&nbsp;each of the
	selling stockholders.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Beneficial ownership is determined in accordance with the rules of the SEC and generally includes any shares over
	which a person exercises sole or shared voting or investment power. Shares of common stock that a person has the right to acquire within 60&nbsp;days of the date of this prospectus are deemed to be outstanding and beneficially owned by such person,
	but are not deemed outstanding for purposes of computing the percentage of beneficial ownership for any other person. Except as indicated by the footnotes below, we believe, based on the information furnished to us, that the persons and entities
	named in the table below have the sole voting and investment power with respect to all common shares that they beneficially own, subject to community property laws where applicable. The percentages of beneficial ownership prior to this offering set
	forth below are based on 78,607,804 shares of our common stock outstanding as of October&nbsp;1, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Except as otherwise indicated in
	the footnotes below, the address of each beneficial owner is c/o&nbsp;AdvancePierre Foods Holdings,&nbsp;Inc., 9987 Carver Road, Blue Ash, Ohio 45242.
</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(1)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	OCM Principal Opportunities Fund IV Delaware,&nbsp;L.P. (&#147;POF IV Delaware&#148;) is the manager of OCM APFH Holdings,&nbsp;LLC (&#147;OCM APFH&#148;). Prior to this offering, POF IV Delaware held 43,268,538 shares,
	or 55.06%, of our common stock, and OCM APFH held 1,667,782 shares, or 2.12%, of our common stock. POF IV Delaware and OCM APFH are offering 9,965,388 and 384,115&nbsp;shares of our common stock, respectively, in this offering. After this offering,
	POF IV Delaware will hold 33,303,150&nbsp;shares, or 42.37%, of our common stock (or 31,732,120&nbsp;shares, or 40.37%, of our common stock if the underwriters exercise in full their option to purchase additional shares of common stock), and OCM
	APFH will hold 1,283,667&nbsp;shares, or 1.63%, of our common stock (or 1,223,112&nbsp;shares, or 1.56%, of our common stock if the underwriters exercise in full their option to purchase additional shares of common stock). The general partner of
	POF&nbsp;IV Delaware is OCM Principal Opportunities Fund&nbsp;IV Delaware&nbsp;GP&nbsp;Inc. (&#147;POF&nbsp;IV Delaware&nbsp;GP&#148;). The general partner of POF&nbsp;IV Delaware&nbsp;GP is OCM Principal Opportunities Fund&nbsp;IV,&nbsp;L.P.
	(&#147;POF&nbsp;IV&#148;). The general partner of POF&nbsp;IV is OCM Principal Opportunities Fund&nbsp;IV&nbsp;GP,&nbsp;L.P. (&#147;POF&nbsp;IV&nbsp;GP&#148;). The general partner of POF&nbsp;IV&nbsp;GP is POF&nbsp;IV&nbsp;GP&nbsp;LTD.
	(&#147;POF&nbsp;IV&nbsp;GP&nbsp;LTD&#148;). The sole shareholder of POF&nbsp;IV&nbsp;GP&nbsp;LTD is Oaktree Fund&nbsp;GP I,&nbsp;L.P. (&#147;GP&nbsp;I&#148;), and the sole director of POF&nbsp;IV&nbsp;GP&nbsp;LTD is OCM&nbsp;LP. The general partner
	of&nbsp;GP&nbsp;I is Oaktree Capital I,&nbsp;L.P. (&#147;Capital I&#148;). The general partner of OCM&nbsp;LP is Oaktree Holdings,&nbsp;Inc. (&#147;Holdings&nbsp;Inc.&#148;). The general partner of Capital I is OCM Holdings I,&nbsp;LLC
	(&#147;Holdings I&#148;). The managing member of Holdings I is Oaktree Holdings,&nbsp;LLC (&#147;Holdings&nbsp;LLC&#148;). The managing member of Holdings&nbsp;LLC and the sole shareholder of Holdings&nbsp;Inc. is Oaktree Capital Group,&nbsp;LLC
	(&#147;OCG&#148;). The duly elected manager of OCG is Oaktree Capital Group Holdings&nbsp;GP,&nbsp;LLC (&#147;OCGH&nbsp;GP&#148;). OCGH&nbsp;GP is managed by an executive committee consisting of Howard S. Marks, Bruce A. Karsh, Jay S. Wintrob, John
	B. Frank, David M. Kirchheimer and Sheldon M. Stone (the &#147;OCGH&nbsp;GP&nbsp;Members&#148;). In such capacity, the OCGH&nbsp;GP&nbsp;Members may be deemed to have indirect beneficial ownership of the shares of our common stock held by POF IV
	Delaware. Each OCGH&nbsp;GP&nbsp;Member disclaims beneficial ownership of the shares of our common stock held by POF IV Delaware.
</TD>

<EFX_CERTAIN_TRANSACTIONS>
<A NAME="FIS_CERTAIN_TRANSACTIONS"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<A NAME="D304963DS1A_HTM_ROM304963_17">
</A>
	CERTAIN RELATIONSHIPS AND RELATED PARTY TRANSACTIONS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Registration Rights Agreement
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Prior to
	our initial public offering, we were party to a registration rights agreement with our principal stockholders and certain other
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pre-initial
</FONT>
	public offering stockholders. In connection with our initial public
	offering, we entered into an amended and restated registration rights agreement with our principal stockholders and the same
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pre-initial
</FONT>
	public offering stockholders. The prior registration rights agreement
	granted, and the amended and restated registration rights agreement grants, to our principal stockholders an unlimited number of &#147;demand&#148; registration rights and to both our principal stockholders and the other
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pre-initial
</FONT>
	public offering stockholders party thereto customary &#147;piggyback&#148; registration rights. The amended and restated registration rights agreement also provides that we will pay certain expenses
	relating to such registrations and indemnify our principal stockholders and the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pre-initial
</FONT>
	public offering stockholders party thereto against certain liabilities which may arise under the Securities Act.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	This offering is a demand registration by our principal stockholders pursuant to the amended and restated registration rights agreement.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Stockholders Agreement
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Prior to our
	initial public offering, we were party to a stockholders agreement with our principal stockholders and certain other
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pre-initial
</FONT>
	public offering stockholders, including members of management, which contained
	agreements among the parties with respect to, among other things, preemptive rights, transfer restrictions,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	come-along
</FONT>
	rights,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	bring-along
</FONT>
	rights, rights of first
	refusal and election of our directors. The
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pre-initial
</FONT>
	public offering stockholders agreement terminated automatically on July&nbsp;20, 2016 upon the consummation of our initial public offering.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In connection with our initial public offering, we entered into a new stockholders agreement with our principal stockholders. This agreement
	grants our principal stockholders the right to nominate to our board of directors a number of designees equal to: (1)&nbsp;at least a majority of the total number of directors comprising our board of directors at such time as long as affiliates of
	Oaktree beneficially own at least 50% of the shares of our common stock entitled to vote generally in the election of our directors; (2)&nbsp;at least 40% of the total number of directors comprising our board of directors at such time as long as
	affiliates of Oaktree beneficially own at least 40% but less than 50% of the shares of our common stock entitled to vote generally in the election of our directors; (3)&nbsp;at least 30% of the total number of directors comprising our board of
	directors at such time as long as affiliates of Oaktree beneficially own at least 30% but less than 40% of the shares of our common stock entitled to vote generally in the election of our directors; (4)&nbsp;at least 20% of the total number of
	directors comprising our board of directors at such time as long as affiliates of Oaktree beneficially own at least 20% but less 30% of the shares of our common stock entitled to vote generally in the election of our directors; and (5)&nbsp;at least
	10% of the total number of directors comprising our board of directors at such time as long as affiliates of Oaktree beneficially own at least 5% but less than 20% of the shares of our common stock entitled to vote generally in the election of our
	directors. For purposes of calculating the number of directors that our principal stockholders are entitled to nominate pursuant to the formula outlined above, any fractional amounts are rounded up to the nearest whole number and the calculation is
	made on a pro forma basis, taking into account any increase in the size of our board of directors (e.g.,&nbsp;one and one quarter (1
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	1
</SUP>
	/
<SUB STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM">
	4
</SUB>
	)
	directors shall equate to two directors). In addition, in the event a vacancy on our board of directors is created by the death, disability, retirement or resignation of an Oaktree director designee, Oaktree has, to the fullest extent permitted by
	law, the right to have the vacancy filled by a new Oaktree
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	director-designee.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Management Services Agreement
	with Oaktree
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Prior to our initial public offering, we were party to a management services agreement with Oaktree pursuant to which
	Oaktree provided us with ongoing management, advisory and consulting services. In
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	128
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage135"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	consideration for the services provided, we were required to pay Oaktree an aggregate annual advisory fee of $3.0&nbsp;million. We were also required to reimburse Oaktree for certain
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	out-of-pocket
</FONT>
</FONT>
	expenses incurred with respect to the performance of services, including fees and expenses paid by Oaktree on our behalf to
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	third-party
</FONT>
	consultants, who were engaged to provide consulting and other advisory services to us in connection with certain performance improvement projects. We paid $14.2&nbsp;million, $11.6&nbsp;million,
	$13.1&nbsp;million and $3.6&nbsp;million in combined fees and expenses to Oaktree in the 2016 YTD period, fiscal 2015, fiscal 2014 and fiscal 2013, respectively. The combined fees and expenses paid to Oaktree in the 2016 YTD period include an
	aggregate success fee of $9.0&nbsp;million, which was paid upon consummation of our initial public offering. On July&nbsp;20, 2016, in connection with our initial public offering, we entered into a termination agreement with Oaktree pursuant to
	which the management services agreement was terminated.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Term Loans
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Oaktree and its affiliates are participating lenders under our first lien term loan. $41.8&nbsp;million aggregate principal amount of our first
	lien term loan was owed to Oaktree and its affiliates at October&nbsp;1, 2016. At October&nbsp;1, 2016, interest accrued to Oaktree and its affiliates was $10,000.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Oaktree and its affiliates were participating lenders under our second lien term loan that was repaid in full on June&nbsp;2, 2016.
	$32.0&nbsp;million aggregate principal amount of our prior second lien term loan was owed to Oaktree and its affiliates at January&nbsp;2, 2016 and January&nbsp;3, 2015. At January&nbsp;2, 2016 and January&nbsp;3, 2015, interest accrued to Oaktree
	and its affiliates was $0.7&nbsp;million and $0.7&nbsp;million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Related party interest for Oaktree and its affiliates was
	$2.0&nbsp;million, $3.1&nbsp;million, $3.1&nbsp;million and $2.9&nbsp;million for the 2016 YTD period, fiscal 2015, fiscal 2014 and fiscal 2013, respectively
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Loans to Executive Officer to Pay Income Taxes
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Prior to our initial public offering, we made from time to time loans, evidenced by promissory notes, to our employees to assist them in paying
	income taxes triggered by restricted share grants and concurrent elections under Section&nbsp;83(b) of the Internal Revenue Code, which result in immediate recognition of compensation for income tax purposes associated with the grants. The employee
	loans typically had terms of seven years and the annual interest rate on the employee loans for each year varied based on the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	mid-term
</FONT>
	adjusted applicable federal rate. The employee loans were secured by all
	shares issued to the respective employee under our 2009 Omnibus Equity Incentive Plan. As of January&nbsp;2, 2016 and January&nbsp;3, 2015, the annual interest rates on the loans ranged from 0.95% to 2.04%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During fiscal 2015, the maximum amounts outstanding, including accrued interest, under loans to Mr.&nbsp;Simons, Mr.&nbsp;Sims,
	Mr.&nbsp;Clough, Mr.&nbsp;Booker, Mr.&nbsp;Schroder, Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle, Mr.&nbsp;Theis, Ms.&nbsp;Panchot and Mr.&nbsp;Hollis were $799,349, $730,865, $340,841, $539,439, $71,985, $314,824, $24,400, $51,295 and $205,068, respectively. During fiscal
	2014, the maximum amounts outstanding, including accrued interest, under loans to Mr.&nbsp;Simons, Mr.&nbsp;Sims, Mr.&nbsp;Clough, Mr.&nbsp;Schroder, Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle, Mr.&nbsp;Theis, Ms.&nbsp;Panchot and Mr.&nbsp;Hollis were $449,421, $659,147,
	$237,787, $70,751, $212,459, $23,957, $18,435 and $73,279, respectively. During fiscal 2013, the maximum amounts outstanding, including accrued interest, under loans to Mr.&nbsp;Simons, Mr.&nbsp;Sims, Mr.&nbsp;Clough, Mr.&nbsp;Schroder,
	Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle, Mr.&nbsp;Theis, Ms.&nbsp;Panchot and Mr.&nbsp;Hollis were $441,544, $647,859, $233,620, $69,522, $172,725, $23,537, $18,139 and $71,995, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In March 2016, Mr.&nbsp;Simons, Mr.&nbsp;Sims, Mr.&nbsp;Clough, Mr.&nbsp;Booker, Mr.&nbsp;Schroder, Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle, Mr.&nbsp;Theis,
	Ms.&nbsp;Panchot and Mr.&nbsp;Hollis repaid their loans in full. We no longer make loans to Mr.&nbsp;Simons, Mr.&nbsp;Sims, Mr.&nbsp;Clough, Mr.&nbsp;Booker, Mr.&nbsp;Schroder, Mr.&nbsp;Chappelle, Mr.&nbsp;Theis, Ms.&nbsp;Panchot and Mr.&nbsp;Hollis
	or our other executive officers or directors.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Indemnification Agreements
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In connection with our initial public offering, we entered into indemnification agreements with each of our executive officers and directors,
	as described under &#147;Description of Capital Stock&#151;Limitations on Liability and Indemnification of Officers and Directors.&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Income Tax
	Receivable Agreement
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We expect to be able to utilize net operating losses, tax basis and certain other tax attributes that arose prior
	to our initial public offering, assuming generation of future income. These net operating loss carryforwards, depreciation and amortization deductions in respect of tax basis and certain other tax attributes will reduce the amount of tax that we and
	our subsidiaries would otherwise be required to pay in the future.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In connection with our initial public offering, we entered into an
	income tax receivable agreement with our
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pre-initial
</FONT>
	public offering stockholders that requires us to pay our
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pre-initial
</FONT>
	public offering stockholders 85% of the amount
	of cash savings, if any, in U.S. federal, state, local, and foreign income tax that we and our subsidiaries actually realize (or are deemed to realize in the case of an early termination by us, a change of control or certain subsidiary dispositions,
	as discussed below) as a result of the utilization of our and our subsidiaries&#146; net operating losses, tax basis and other tax attributes attributable to periods prior to our initial public offering together with interest accrued at a rate of
	LIBOR plus 2% from the date the applicable tax return is due (without extension) until the date the applicable payment is due. To the extent that we fail to make payments when due under the income tax receivable agreement for any reason, other than
	as a result of certain restrictions in our debt documents, discussed below, such payments will accrue interest at a rate of LIBOR plus 5% per annum until paid.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For purposes of the income tax receivable agreement, cash savings in income tax is computed by comparing our actual income tax liability to
	the amount of such taxes that we would have been required to pay had we not been able to utilize the tax benefits subject to the income tax receivable agreement. The term of the income tax receivable agreement commenced upon consummation of our
	initial public offering and will continue until all relevant tax benefits have been utilized or have expired.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our counterparties under
	the income tax receivable agreement are not required to reimburse us for any benefits that are subsequently disallowed (although any future payments would be adjusted to the extent possible to reflect the result of such disallowance). As a result,
	in such circumstances we could make payments under the income tax receivable agreement that are greater than our actual cash tax savings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	While the actual amount and timing of any payments under the income tax receivable agreement will vary depending upon a number of factors,
	including the amount, character and timing of our and our subsidiaries&#146; taxable income in the future, we expect that the payments made under the income tax receivable agreement during its term could be material. Assuming no material changes in
	the relevant tax law, and that we and our subsidiaries earn sufficient taxable income to realize the full tax benefits subject to the income tax receivable agreement, we expect that future payments under the income tax receivable agreement will
	total approximately $254.2&nbsp;million. On July&nbsp;20, 2016, the effective date of the income tax receivable agreement, we recorded an initial obligation of approximately $254.2&nbsp;million. We expect to make the first payment during the fourth
	quarter of 2017, and we estimate that such payment will be approximately $26.7&nbsp;million plus interest at LIBOR plus 2% for the period April&nbsp;15, 2017 through the date of payment. We expect to pay approximately half of the estimated value of
	the income tax receivable agreement payments in the first four years
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	(2017-2020)
</FONT>
	and the balance between 2021 and 2055.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	If we undergo a change of control, the income tax receivable agreement will terminate, and we will be required to make a lump sum payment
	equal to the present value of future payments under the income tax receivable agreement, which payment would be based on certain assumptions (the &#147;valuation assumptions&#148;),
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	130
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage137"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	including those relating to our and our subsidiaries&#146; future taxable income. Additionally, if we or a direct or indirect subsidiary transfers any asset to a corporation with which we do not
	file&nbsp;a consolidated tax return, we will be treated as having sold that asset in a taxable transaction for purposes of determining the cash savings in income tax under the income tax receivable agreement. If we sell or otherwise dispose of any
	of our subsidiaries in a transaction that is not a change of control, we will be required to make a lump sum payment equal to the present value of future payments under the income tax receivable agreement attributable to the tax benefits of such
	subsidiary that is sold or disposed of, applying the valuation assumptions. Any such payment resulting from a change of control, asset transfer or subsidiary disposition could be substantial and could exceed our actual cash tax savings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The income tax receivable agreement provides that in the event that we breach any of our material obligations under it, whether as a result of
	our failure to make any payment when due (subject to a specified cure period), failure to honor any other material obligation under it or by operation of law as a result of the rejection of it in a case commenced under the United States Bankruptcy
	Code or otherwise, then all our payment and other obligations under the income tax receivable agreement will be accelerated and will become due and payable, applying the same valuation assumptions discussed above, including those relating to our
	future taxable income. Such payments could be substantial and could exceed our actual cash tax savings. Additionally, we generally have the right to terminate the income tax receivable agreement. If we terminate the income tax receivable agreement,
	our payment and other obligations under the income tax receivable agreement will be accelerated and will become due and payable, also applying the valuation assumptions discussed above. Such payments could be substantial and could exceed our actual
	cash tax savings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Because we are a holding company with no operations of our own, our ability to make payments under the income tax
	receivable agreement is dependent on the ability of our subsidiaries to make distributions to us. To the extent that we are unable to make payments under the income tax receivable agreement as a result of specified restrictions in our, or our
	subsidiaries&#146;, debt documents, such payments will be deferred and will accrue interest at a rate of LIBOR plus 2% per annum until paid. To the extent that we otherwise are not able to make payment when due under the income tax receivable
	agreement, such late payments will accrue interest at the rate of LIBOR plus 5% per annum until paid. We have agreed under the income tax receivable agreement not to incur, and not to permit any of our subsidiaries to incur, any new restrictions,
	enter into any agreement or indenture or any amendment or other modification to any agreement or indenture (including, in each case, in connection with any refinancing) that would directly or indirectly, materially limit our ability to make payments
	under the income tax receivable agreement or the ability of our subsidiaries to make payments to us for that purpose. Additionally, we have agreed under the income tax receivable agreement not to, without the consent (not to be unreasonably
	withheld) of the representative of our
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	pre-initial
</FONT>
	public offering stockholders, (1)&nbsp;change any accounting method, or amend or take any position inconsistent with a prior tax return if such action could
	materially adversely affect the assets included in the income tax receivable agreement, (2)&nbsp;seek any guidance from, or initiate any communication with, the Internal Revenue Service or any other taxing authority (whether written, verbal or
	otherwise) at any time on matters concerning the assets included in the income tax receivable agreement, or (3)&nbsp;settle or otherwise resolve any audit or other challenge by a taxing authority of a material amount relating to any realized benefit
	under the income tax receivable agreement.
</P>
</EFX_CERTAIN_TRANSACTIONS>
<EFX_CERTAIN_TRANSACTIONS>
<A NAME="FIS_CERTAIN_TRANSACTIONS_2"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Policies and Procedures for Related Person Transactions
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our board of directors recognizes that transactions with related persons present a heightened risk of conflicts of interests and improper
	valuation (or the perception thereof), and has a written policy on transactions with related persons that is in conformity with the requirements upon issuers having
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	publicly-held
</FONT>
	common stock that is listed on
	the NYSE. Under the policy:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	any related person transaction, and any material amendment or modification to a related person transaction, must be reviewed and approved or ratified by a committee of our board of directors composed solely of
	independent directors who are disinterested or by the disinterested members of our board of directors; and
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	131
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage138"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	any employment relationship or transaction involving an executive officer and any related compensation must be approved by our Compensation Committee or recommended by our Compensation Committee to our board of
	directors for its approval.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In connection with the review and approval or ratification of a related person transaction:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	management must disclose to the committee or disinterested directors, as applicable, the name of the related person and the basis on which the person is a related person, the material terms of the related person
	transaction, including the approximate dollar value of the amount involved in the transaction, and all the material facts as to the related person&#146;s direct or indirect interest in, or relationship to, the related person transaction;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	management must advise the committee or disinterested directors, as applicable, as to whether the related person transaction complies with the terms of our agreements governing our material outstanding indebtedness that
	limit or restrict our ability to enter into a related person transaction;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	management must advise the committee or disinterested directors, as applicable, as to whether the related person transaction will be required to be disclosed in our applicable filings under the Securities Act or the
	Exchange Act, and related rules, and, to the extent required to be disclosed, management must ensure that the related person transaction is disclosed in accordance with such Acts and related rules; and
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	management must advise the committee or disinterested directors, as applicable, as to whether the related person transaction constitutes a &#147;personal loan&#148; for purposes of Section&nbsp;402 of the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Sarbanes-Oxley
</FONT>
	Act.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In addition, the related person transaction policy provides that the
	committee or disinterested directors, as applicable, in connection with any approval or ratification of a related person transaction involving a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-employee
</FONT>
	director or director nominee, should consider
	whether such transaction would compromise the director or director nominee&#146;s status as an &#147;independent,&#148; &#147;outside,&#148; or
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	&#147;non-employee&#148;
</FONT>
	director, as applicable, under the rules
	and regulations of the SEC, the NYSE and the Internal Revenue Code.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	132

<EFX_SECURITIES_DESCRIPTION>
<A NAME="FIS_SECURITIES_DESCRIPTION"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<A NAME="D304963DS1A_HTM_ROM304963_18">
</A>
	DESCRIPTION OF CERTAIN INDEBTEDNESS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We summarize the principal terms of some of the agreements governing our existing indebtedness below. The following summaries are not complete
	descriptions of all of the terms of such agreements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Senior Notes
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On December 7, 2016, we issued $400 million aggregate principal amount of our 5.50% senior notes due 2024, in a private placement to
	&#147;qualified institutional buyers&#148; as defined in Rule 144A under the Securities Act and outside the United States to non-U.S. persons pursuant to Regulation S under the Securities Act. The notes were issued pursuant to an indenture, dated as
	of December 7, 2016 (the &#147;Indenture&#148;), by and among us, the guarantors named therein and U.S. Bank National Association, as trustee. The notes will mature on December 15, 2024.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Interest
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Interest
	on the notes will accrue at a rate of 5.50% per annum and will be paid semi-annually on June&nbsp;15 and December&nbsp;15 of each year, commencing on June 15, 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Guarantees; Ranking
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The notes are our unsecured senior obligations and are guaranteed, jointly and severally, on a senior unsecured basis, by all of our existing
	subsidiaries. The notes will be guaranteed by our future restricted subsidiaries to the extent such subsidiaries guarantee or become a borrower under our credit facilities or guarantee future capital markets debt securities. These guarantees are
	subject to release under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Optional Redemption
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At any time prior to December 15, 2019, we may redeem the notes, at our discretion, in whole or in part, for cash at a redemption price equal
	to 100% of the principal amount of the notes, plus the applicable make-whole premium set forth in the Indenture, plus accrued and unpaid interest, if any, to, but not including, the applicable redemption date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On or after December 15, 2019, we may redeem the notes, at our discretion, in whole or in part, for cash at a redemption price equal to 100%
	of the principal amount of the notes, plus accrued and unpaid interest, if any, to, but not including, the applicable redemption date, plus a premium declining over time as set forth in the Indenture.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Change of Control
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Upon the occurrence of certain change of control transactions, we will be required to offer to repurchase the notes at 101% of their principal
	amount, plus accrued and unpaid interest, if any, to, but not including, the repurchase date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Equity Clawback
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Prior to December 15, 2019, we may redeem up to 40% of the aggregate principal amount of the notes with proceeds from certain equity offerings
	at a redemption price equal to 105.50% of the aggregate principal amount thereof, plus accrued and unpaid interest, if any, to, but not including, the applicable redemption date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	133
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage140"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Covenants
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Indenture contains covenants that, among other things, restrict our ability and the ability of our restricted subsidiaries to (1) incur or
	guarantee additional indebtedness or issue disqualified stock or preferred stock; (2) incur restrictions on the payment of dividends or other distributions from restricted subsidiaries that are not guarantors; (3) create or incur certain liens; (4)
	make certain investments; (5) transfer or sell assets; (6) engage in transactions with affiliates; (7) merge or consolidate with other companies or transfer all or substantially all of its assets; or (8) pay dividends or make other restricted
	payments. These covenants are subject to a number of limitations and exceptions set forth in the Indenture.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Events of Default
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Indenture also provides for customary events of default, including failure to pay any principal or interest when due, failure
	to comply with covenants and cross acceleration provisions. In the case of an event of default arising from specified events of bankruptcy or insolvency, all outstanding notes will become due and payable immediately without further action or notice.
	If any other event of default under the Indenture occurs or is continuing, the trustee or holders of at least 30% in aggregate principal amount of the then outstanding notes may declare all of the notes to be due and payable immediately.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	First Lien Term Loan
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On June&nbsp;2,
	2016, we, our wholly owned indirect subsidiary, APF, and our wholly owned direct subsidiary, APF Holdco, entered into a first lien credit agreement with Morgan Stanley Senior Funding,&nbsp;Inc., as administrative agent, and the lenders from time to
	time party thereto, providing for a first lien term loan in an aggregate principal amount of $1.30&nbsp;billion, the proceeds of which were used to repay our prior term loans, to pay related accrued interest and to pay related expenses. As of
	October&nbsp;1, 2016, after giving effect to the issuance of the notes and the use of proceeds therefrom, $695.0 million would have been outstanding under our first lien term loan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Maturity; Prepayments
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our first lien term loan will mature on June&nbsp;2, 2023. Principal repayments of 0.25% of the initial principal amount of our first lien term
	loan (approximately $3.25&nbsp;million), subject to reduction for certain other prepayments, are payable quarterly, with the balance due at maturity. As a result of the voluntary prepayment of $205.0 million of our first lien term loan with a
	portion of the proceeds of our initial public offering and after giving effect to the issuance of the notes and the use of proceeds therefrom, the only required future payment under our first lien term loan is a single payment of $695.0 million at
	maturity, which is currently June&nbsp;2, 2023.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In addition to the quarterly principal payments, our first lien term loan is subject to
	mandatory prepayment (1)&nbsp;upon any incurrence of indebtedness by us or any of our restricted subsidiaries, other than indebtedness permitted to be incurred or issued under our first lien term loan, (2)&nbsp;upon certain specified asset sales,
	dispositions by us and our restricted subsidiaries and casualty events, in each case, subject to certain thresholds and reinvestment provisions and (3)&nbsp;once per fiscal year in an amount equal to 50% (subject to reduction to 25% upon achieving a
	total net leverage ratio (as defined in our first lien term loan) of 3.95 to 1.00 and further reduction to 0% upon achieving a total net leverage ratio of 3.45 to 1.00) of annual excess cash flow (as defined in our first lien term loan, and subject
	to reduction for cash used for capital expenditures, acquisitions and certain other permitted investments, certain debt repayments and redemptions and certain permitted dividends in each case except to the extent financed with certain indebtedness).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	APF may prepay our first lien term loan at any time and from time to time, in whole or in part, without premium or penalty.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	134
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage141"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D304963DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Guarantees; Security
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The obligations of APF under our first lien term loan are guaranteed by us, APF Holdco and each of APF&#146;s direct and indirect wholly owned
	domestic subsidiaries (other than subsidiaries of foreign subsidiaries, immaterial subsidiaries, unrestricted subsidiaries and certain other exceptions). Our first lien term loan and the guarantees thereunder are secured by liens granted by APF and
	the guarantors in (1)&nbsp;all of the capital stock of all direct domestic subsidiaries, (2)&nbsp;65% of the capital stock of each direct foreign subsidiary and (3)&nbsp;substantially all other tangible and intangible assets, subject in each case to
	certain exceptions. The liens securing our first lien term loan (1)&nbsp;have priority over the liens securing our ABL facility with respect to the Term Loan Priority Collateral (as defined in our first lien term loan) and (2)&nbsp;are second in
	priority with respect to the ABL Priority Collateral (as defined in our first lien term loan).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Interest; Fees
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As a result of the repricing of our first lien term loan on December 7, 2016, our first lien term loan bears interest equal to the alternative
	base rate plus 2.00% per annum or LIBOR plus 3.00% per annum, with a LIBOR floor of 1.00%, based on a periodic election of LIBOR or base rate by APF. At October&nbsp;1, 2016, prior to giving effect to the repricing of our first lien term loan, the
	interest rate for all borrowings on our first lien term loan was 4.5%.&nbsp;At October&nbsp;1, 2016, after giving effect to the repricing of our first lien term loan, the interest rate for all borrowings on our first lien term loan would have been
	4.0%.&nbsp;As a result of the repricing of our first lien term loan on December 7, 2016, a 1.0% mandatory prepayment premium will apply to certain repricing transactions occurring prior to the six-month anniversary of such date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	APF pays customary fees in respect of our first lien term loan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Covenants
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our
	first lien term loan contains a number of covenants that, among other things, limit or restrict the ability of us and our restricted subsidiaries to: (1)&nbsp;dispose of certain assets; (2)&nbsp;incur, permit or guarantee additional indebtedness;
	(3)&nbsp;enter into a new line of business; (4)&nbsp;make investments; (5)&nbsp;incur or maintain liens; (6)&nbsp;modify certain terms of their organizational documents or certain debt instruments; (7)&nbsp;permit restrictions on a restricted
	subsidiary&#146;s ability to pay dividends, make intercompany loans or otherwise transfer assets to us or any of our restricted subsidiaries; (8)&nbsp;engage in certain transactions with affiliates; (9)&nbsp;engage in mergers or the sale of
	substantially all of its assets; or (10)&nbsp;pay dividends or make other restricted payments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At October&nbsp;1, 2016, we and our
	restricted subsidiaries were in compliance with all covenants under our first lien term loan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Events of Default
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our first lien term loan contains a number of events of default including
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-payment
</FONT>
	of principal,
	interest or fees, violation of covenants, material inaccuracy of representations or warranties, cross payment default and cross acceleration to certain other material indebtedness, certain bankruptcy events, certain ERISA events, invalidity of
	guarantees or security interests, material judgments and change of control.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	ABL Facility
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On June&nbsp;2, 2016, our wholly owned indirect subsidiary, APF, entered into a third amendment to the second amended and restated credit
	agreement with Wells Fargo Capital Finance,&nbsp;LLC, as administrative agent, and the lenders from time to time party thereto. Our ABL facility provides for an asset based senior secured revolving loan facility for aggregate maximum borrowings
	(subject to availability under a borrowing base) of up to $175&nbsp;million to APF. $30&nbsp;million of our ABL facility is available for the issuance of letters of credit. As of October&nbsp;1, 2016, APF had $5.3&nbsp;million of letters of credit
	outstanding under our ABL facility. There was available capacity under our ABL facility of $130.2&nbsp;million at October&nbsp;1, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	135
</P>

</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Maturity; Prepayments
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The maturity date of our ABL facility is June&nbsp;2, 2021.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Subject to certain exceptions, our ABL facility is subject to mandatory prepayment if outstanding extensions of credit exceed the borrowing
	base. The amount of the mandatory prepayment is the amount by which certain outstanding extensions of credit exceed the borrowing base.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Guarantees; Security
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The obligations of APF under our ABL facility are guaranteed by us, APF Holdco and each of APF&#146;s direct and indirect wholly owned domestic
	subsidiaries (other than subsidiaries of foreign subsidiaries, immaterial subsidiaries, unrestricted subsidiaries and certain other exceptions). Our ABL facility and the guarantees thereunder are secured by security interests in (1)&nbsp;all of the
	capital stock of all direct domestic subsidiaries, (2)&nbsp;65% of the capital stock of each direct foreign subsidiary and (3)&nbsp;substantially all other tangible and intangible assets, subject in each case to certain exceptions. The liens
	securing our ABL facility (1)&nbsp;have priority over the liens securing our first lien term loan with respect to the ABL Priority Collateral and (2)&nbsp;are second in priority with respect to the Term Loan Priority Collateral.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Interest; Fees
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	APF can periodically elect to pay interest on outstanding borrowings under our ABL facility at an alternative base rate plus a margin ranging
	from 0.50% to 1.00% per annum or LIBOR plus a margin ranging from 1.50% to 2.0% per annum, in each case, depending on APF&#146;s average excess availability under our ABL facility for the most recently completed calendar quarter. Our ABL facility
	also carries a fronting fee with respect to letters of credit of 0.125% per annum and an unused commitment fee ranging from 0.250% to 0.375% per annum.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	APF pays other customary fees in respect of our ABL facility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Covenants
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our ABL
	facility contains a number of covenants that, among other things, limit or restrict the ability of us and our restricted subsidiaries to: (1)&nbsp;dispose of certain assets; (2)&nbsp;incur or guarantee additional indebtedness; (3)&nbsp;enter into a
	new line of business; (4)&nbsp;make investments or certain payments in respect of indebtedness; (5)&nbsp;incur or maintain liens; (6)&nbsp;modify certain terms of their organizational documents or certain debt instruments; (7)&nbsp;permit
	restrictions on a restricted subsidiary&#146;s ability to pay dividends, make intercompany loans or otherwise transfer assets to us or any of our restricted subsidiaries; (8)&nbsp;engage in certain transactions with affiliates; or (9)&nbsp;engage in
	mergers or the sale of substantially all of its assets; or (10)&nbsp;pay dividends or make other restricted payments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At October&nbsp;1,
	2016, we and our restricted subsidiaries were in compliance with all covenants under our ABL facility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	Events of Default
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">

</FONT>

	principal, interest or fees, violation of covenants, material inaccuracy of representations or warranties, cross payment default and cross acceleration to certain other material indebtedness, certain bankruptcy events, certain ERISA events,

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<A NAME="D304963DS1A_HTM_ROM304963_19">
</A>
	DESCRIPTION OF CAPITAL STOCK
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following is a description of the material terms of, and is qualified in its entirety by, our amended and restated certificate of
	incorporation and amended and restated bylaws, copies of which are filed as exhibits to the registration statement of which this prospectus is a part.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our purpose is to engage in any lawful act or activity for which corporations may now or hereafter be organized under the DGCL. Our authorized
	capital stock consists of 500,000,000 shares of common stock, par value $0.01 per share, and 50,000,000 shares of preferred stock, par value $0.01 per share. No shares of preferred stock are issued or outstanding as of the date of this prospectus.
	Unless our board of directors determines otherwise, we will issue all shares of our capital stock in uncertificated form.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Common Stock
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Holders of our common stock are entitled to one vote for each share held of record on all matters to which stockholders are entitled to vote
	generally, including the election or removal of directors. The holders of our common stock do not have cumulative voting rights in the election of directors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Upon our liquidation, dissolution or winding up and after payment in full of all amounts required to be paid to creditors and to the holders
	of preferred stock having liquidation preferences, if any, the holders of our common stock will be entitled to receive pro rata our remaining assets and funds available for distribution. Holders of our common stock do not have preemptive,
	subscription or conversion rights. The common stock will not be subject to further calls or assessment by us. There will be no redemption or sinking fund provisions applicable to the common stock. All shares of our common stock that will be
	outstanding at the time of the completion of the offering will be fully paid and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-assessable.
</FONT>
	The rights, powers, preferences and privileges of holders of our common stock will be subject to those of the
	holders of any shares of our preferred stock we may authorize and issue in the future.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Preferred Stock
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our amended and restated certificate of incorporation authorizes our board of directors to establish one or more series of preferred stock
	(including convertible preferred stock). Unless required by law or by the NYSE, the authorized shares of preferred stock will be available for issuance without further action by you. Our board of directors is able to determine, with respect to any
	series of preferred stock, the powers (including voting powers), preferences and relative participations, optional or other special rights, and the qualifications, limitations or restrictions thereof, of that series, including, without limitation:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
